<!-- STANDARDS -->
<div>
<div id="adaCh1">
<h1 id="a1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Chapter 1: Application and Administration[-END TRANSLATE-]</h1>
<h2 id="ada-101">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]101 Purpose[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-101_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]101.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]This document contains scoping and technical requirements for accessibility to sites, facilities, buildings, and elements by individuals with disabilities.  The requirements are to be applied during the design, construction, additions to, and alteration of sites, facilities, buildings, and elements to the extent required by regulations issued by Federal agencies under the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990 (ADA).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 101.1 General.  In addition to these requirements, covered entities must comply with the regulations issued by the Department of Justice and the Department of Transportation under the Americans with Disabilities Act.  There are issues affecting individuals with disabilities which are not addressed by these requirements, but which are covered by the Department of Justice and the Department of Transportation regulations.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-101_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]101.2 Effect on Removal of Barriers in Existing Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]This document does not address existing facilities unless altered at the discretion of a covered entity.  The Department of Justice has authority over existing facilities that are subject to the requirement for removal of barriers under title III of the ADA.  Any determination that this document applies to existing facilities subject to the barrier removal requirement is solely within the discretion of the Department of Justice and is effective only to the extent required by regulations issued by the Department of Justice.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-102">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]102 Dimensions for Adults and Children[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The technical requirements are based on adult dimensions and anthropometrics.  In addition, this document includes technical requirements based on children’s dimensions and anthropometrics for drinking fountains, water closets, toilet compartments, lavatories and sinks, dining surfaces, and work surfaces.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-103">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]103 Equivalent Facilitation[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Nothing in these requirements prevents the use of designs, products, or technologies as alternatives to those prescribed, provided they result in substantially equivalent or greater accessibility and usability.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 103 Equivalent Facilitation.  The responsibility for demonstrating equivalent facilitation in the event of a challenge rests with the covered entity.  With the exception of transit facilities, which are covered by regulations issued by the Department of Transportation, there is no process for certifying that an alternative design provides equivalent facilitation.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-104">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]104 Conventions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-104_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]104.1 Dimensions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Dimensions that are not stated as “maximum” or “minimum” are absolute.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-104_1_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]104.1.1 Construction and Manufacturing Tolerances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]All dimensions are subject to conventional industry tolerances except where the requirement is stated as a range with specific minimum and maximum end points.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div id="ada-104_1_1_advisory" class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 104.1.1 Construction and Manufacturing Tolerances.  Conventional industry tolerances recognized by this provision include those for field conditions and those that may be a necessary consequence of a particular manufacturing process. Recognized tolerances are not intended to apply to design work.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]It is good practice when specifying dimensions to avoid specifying a tolerance where dimensions are absolute.  For example, if this document requires “1 inches,” avoid specifying “1 inches plus or minus X inches.”[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where the requirement states a specified range, such as in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-609_4" class="navSectionLink">609.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]where grab bars must be installed between 33 inches and 36 inches above the floor, the range provides an adequate tolerance and therefore no tolerance outside of the range at either end point is permitted.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where a requirement is a minimum or a maximum dimension that does not have two specific minimum and maximum end points, tolerances may apply.  Where an element is to be installed at the minimum or maximum permitted dimension, such as “15 inches minimum” or “5 pounds maximum”, it would not be good practice to specify “5 pounds (plus X pounds) or 15 inches (minus X inches).”  Rather, it would be good practice to specify a dimension less than the required maximum (or more than the required minimum) by the amount of the expected field or manufacturing tolerance and not to state any tolerance in conjunction with the specified dimension.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Specifying dimensions in design in the manner described above will better ensure that facilities and elements accomplish the level of accessibility intended by these requirements.  It will also more often produce an end result of strict and literal compliance with the stated requirements and eliminate enforcement difficulties and issues that might otherwise arise.  Information on specific tolerances may be available from industry or trade organizations, code groups and building officials, and published references.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h3 id="ada-104_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]104.2 Calculation of Percentages[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where the required number of elements or facilities to be provided is determined by calculations of ratios or percentages and remainders or fractions result, the next greater whole number of such elements or facilities shall be provided.  Where the determination of the required size or dimension of an element or facility involves ratios or percentages, rounding down for values less than one half shall be permitted.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-104_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]104.3 Figures[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Unless specifically stated otherwise, figures are provided for informational purposes only.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
{% include_cached figure-caption.html
text=[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-] "Figure 104: Graphic Convention for Figure"[-END TRANSLATE-]
img-file= "ADA-AB1.gif"
img-alt=[-ALT BEGIN TRANSLATE-] "Las líneas de dimensión muestran las unidades inglesas por encima de la línea (en pulgadas a menos que se indique lo contrario) y las unidades SI (en milímetros a menos que se indique lo contrario). Las pequeñas mediciones muestran la cota con una flecha que apunta a la línea de cota.Los rangos de dimensión se muestran por encima de la línea en pulgadas y por debajo de la línea en milímetros.  "Min" se refiere al mínimo, y "max" se refiere al máximo.  Los símbolos matemáticos indican mayor que, mayor que o igual a, menor que, y menor que o igual a.  Una línea discontinua identifica el límite del espacio libre del piso o el espacio de maniobra.Una línea con disparo alterno y guiones largos con una "C" y una "L" al final indican la línea central.  Una línea discontinua con espacios más largos indica un elemento permitido o su extensión.  Una flecha es para identificar la dirección de viaje o aproximación.  Una línea negra gruesa se utiliza para representar una pared, piso, techo u otro elemento cortado en sección o plano.  El sombreado gris se utiliza para mostrar un elemento en elevación o planta.  El rayado se utiliza para mostrar la zona de ubicación de elementos, controles o entidades.  Los términos definidos por este documento se muestran en cursiva." [-END TRANSLATE-]

Dimension lines show English units above the line (in inches unless otherwise noted) and the SI units (in millimeters unless otherwise noted).  Small measurements show the dimension with an arrow pointing to the dimension line.  Dimension ranges are shown above the line in inches and below the line in millimeters.  “Min” refers to minimum, and “max” refers to the maximum.  Mathematical symbols indicate greater than, greater than or equal to, less than, and less than or equal to.  A dashed line identifies the boundary of clear floor space or maneuvering space.  A line with alternating shot and long dashes with a “C” and “L” at the end indicate the centerline.  A dashed line with longer spaces indicates a permitted element or its extension.  An arrow is to identify the direction of travel or approach.  A thick black line is used to represent a wall, floor, ceiling or other element cut in section or plan.  Gray shading is used to show an element in elevation or plan.  Hatching is used to show the location zone of elements, controls, or features.  Terms defined by this document are shown in italics

"[-END TRANSLATE-]
%}
<h2 id="ada-105">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]105 Referenced Standards[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-105_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]105.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The standards listed in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-105_2" class="navSectionLink">105.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]are incorporated by reference in this document and are part of the requirements to the prescribed extent of each such reference.  The Director of the Federal Register has approved these standards for incorporation by reference in accordance with 5 U.S.C. 552(a) and 1 CFR part 51.  Copies of the referenced standards may be inspected at the Architectural and Transportation Barriers Compliance Board, 1331 F Street, NW, Suite 1000, Washington, DC  20004; at the Department of Justice, Civil Rights Division, Disability Rights Section, 1425 New York Avenue, NW, Washington, DC; at the Department of Transportation, 400 Seventh Street, SW, Room 10424, Washington DC; or at the National Archives and Records Administration (NARA).  For information on the availability of this material at NARA, call 202-741-6030, or go to[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="http://www.archives.gov/federal_register/code_of_federal_regulations/ibr_locations.html">http://www.archives.gov/federal [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]register/code of federal regulations/ibr locations.html[-END TRANSLATE-]</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-105_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]105.2 Referenced Standards[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The specific edition of the standards listed below are referenced in this document.  Where differences occur between this document and the referenced standards, this document applies.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-105_2_1">105.2.1 ANSI/BHMA</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Copies of the referenced standards may be obtained from the Builders Hardware Manufacturers Association, 355 Lexington Avenue, 17th floor, New York, NY 10017[-END TRANSLATE-] (<a href="http://www.buildershardware.com/">http://www.buildershardware.com</a>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ANSI/BHMA A156.10-1999 American National Standard for Power Operated Pedestrian Doors (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404_3" class="navSectionLink">404.3</a>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ANSI/BHMA A156.19-1997 American National Standard for Power Assist and Low Energy Power Operated Doors (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404_3" class="navSectionLink">404.3</a>, <a href="#ada-408_3_2_1" class="navSectionLink">408.3.2.1</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-409_3_1" class="navSectionLink">409.3.1</a>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ANSI/BHMA A156.19-2002 American National Standard for Power Assist and Low Energy Power Operated Doors (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404_3" class="navSectionLink">404.3</a>, <a href="#ada-408_3_2_1" class="navSectionLink">408.3.2.1</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-409_3_1" class="navSectionLink">409.3.1</a>).</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 105.2.1 ANSI/BHMA.  ANSI/BHMA A156.10-1999 applies to power operated doors for pedestrian use which open automatically when approached by pedestrians.  Included are provisions intended to reduce the chance of user injury or entrapment.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ANSI/BHMA A156.19-1997 and A156.19-2002 applies to power assist doors, low energy power operated doors or low energy power open doors for pedestrian use not provided for in ANSI/BHMA A156.10 for Power Operated Pedestrian Doors.  Included are provisions intended to reduce the chance of user injury or entrapment.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-105_2_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]105.2.2 ASME</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Copies of the referenced standards may be obtained from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, Three Park Avenue, New York, New York 10016[-END TRANSLATE-] (<strong><a href="http://www.asme.org/">http://www.asme.org</a></strong>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASME A17.1-2000 Safety Code for Elevators and Escalators, including ASME A17.1a-2002 Addenda and ASME A17.1b-2003 Addenda (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-407_1" class="navSectionLink">407.1</a>, <a href="#ada-408_1" class="navSectionLink">408.1</a>, <a href="#ada-409_1" class="navSectionLink">409.1</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-810_9" class="navSectionLink">810.9</a>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASME A18.1-1999 Safety Standard for Platform Lifts and Stairway Chairlifts, including ASME A18.1a-2001 Addenda and ASME A18.1b-2001 Addenda (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-410_1" class="navSectionLink">410.1</a>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASME A18.1-2003 Safety Standard for Platform Lifts and Stairway Chairlifts, (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-410_1" class="navSectionLink">410.1</a>).</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 105.2.2 ASME.  ASME A17.1-2000 is used by local jurisdictions throughout the United States for the design, construction, installation, operation, inspection, testing, maintenance, alteration, and repair of elevators and escalators.  The majority of the requirements apply to the operational machinery not seen or used by elevator passengers.  ASME A17.1 requires a two-way means of emergency communications in passenger elevators.  This means of communication must connect with emergency or authorized personnel and not an automated answering system.  The communication system must be push button activated.  The activation button must be permanently identified with the word “HELP.”  A visual indication acknowledging the establishment of a communications link to authorized personnel must be provided.  The visual indication must remain on until the call is terminated by authorized personnel.  The building location, the elevator car number, and the need for assistance must be provided to authorized personnel answering the emergency call.  The use of a handset by the communications system is prohibited.  Only the authorized personnel answering the call can terminate the call.  Operating instructions for the communications system must be provided in the elevator car.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The provisions for escalators require that at least two flat steps be provided at the entrance and exit of every escalator and that steps on escalators be demarcated by yellow lines 2 inches wide maximum along the back and sides of steps.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASME A18.1-1999 and ASME A18.1-2003 address the design, construction, installation, operation, inspection, testing, maintenance and repair of lifts that are intended for transportation of persons with disabilities.  Lifts are classified as: vertical platform lifts, inclined platform lifts, inclined stairway chairlifts, private residence vertical platform lifts, private residence inclined platform lifts, and private residence inclined stairway chairlifts.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]This document does not permit the use of inclined stairway chairlifts which do not provide platforms because such lifts require the user to transfer to a seat.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASME A18.1 contains requirements for runways, which are the spaces in which platforms or seats move.  The standard includes additional provisions for runway enclosures, electrical equipment and wiring, structural support, headroom clearance (which is 80 inches minimum), lower level access ramps and pits.  The enclosure walls not used for entry or exit are required to have a grab bar the full length of the wall on platform lifts.  Access ramps are required to meet requirements similar to those for ramps in Chapter 4 of this document.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Each of the lift types addressed in ASME A18.1 must meet requirements for capacity, load, speed, travel, operating devices, and control equipment.  The maximum permitted height for operable parts is consistent with Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-308" class="navSectionLink">308</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of this document.  The standard also addresses attendant operation.  However, Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-410_1" class="navSectionLink">410.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of this document does not permit attendant operation.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-105_2_">105.2.3 ASTM</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Copies of the referenced standards may be obtained from the American Society for Testing and Materials, 100 Bar Harbor Drive, West Conshohocken, Pennsylvania 19428 [-END TRANSLATE-](<strong><a href="http://www.astm.org/">http://www.astm.org</a></strong>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASTM F 1292-99 Standard Specification for Impact Attenuation of Surface Systems Under and Around Playground Equipment (see 1008.2.6.2).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASTM F 1292-04 Standard Specification for Impact Attenuation of Surfacing Materials Within the Use Zone of Playground Equipment (see 1008.2.6.2).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASTM F 1487-01 Standard Consumer Safety Performance Specification for Playground Equipment for Public Use (see 106.5).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASTM F 1951-99 Standard Specification for Determination of Accessibility of Surface Systems Under and Around Playground Equipment (see 1008.2.6.1).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 105.2.3 ASTM.  ASTM F 1292-99 and ASTM F 1292-04 establish a uniform means to measure and compare characteristics of surfacing materials to determine whether materials provide a safe surface under and around playground equipment.  These standards are referenced in the play areas requirements of this document when an accessible surface is required inside a play area use zone where a fall attenuating surface is also required.  The standards cover the minimum impact attenuation requirements, when tested in accordance with Test Method F 355, for surface systems to be used under and around any piece of playground equipment from which a person may fall.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASTM F 1487-01 establishes a nationally recognized safety standard for public playground equipment to address injuries identified by the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission.  It defines the use zone, which is the ground area beneath and immediately adjacent to a play structure or play equipment designed for unrestricted circulation around the equipment and on whose surface it is predicted that a user would land when falling from or exiting a play structure or equipment.  The play areas requirements in this document reference the ASTM F 1487 standard when defining accessible routes that overlap use zones requiring fall attenuating surfaces.  If the use zone of a playground is not entirely surfaced with an accessible material, at least one accessible route within the use zone must be provided from the perimeter to all accessible play structures or components within the playground.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]ASTM F 1951-99 establishes a uniform means to measure the characteristics of surface systems in order to provide performance specifications to select materials for use as an accessible surface under and around playground equipment.  Surface materials that comply with this standard and are located in the use zone must also comply with ASTM F 1292.  The test methods in this standard address access for children and adults who may traverse the surfacing to aid children who are playing.  When a surface is tested it must have an average work per foot value for straight propulsion and for turning less than the average work per foot values for straight propulsion and for turning, respectively, on a hard, smooth surface with a grade of 7% (1:14).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-105_2_">105.2.4 ICC/IBC</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Copies of the referenced standard may be obtained from the International Code Council, 5203 Leesburg Pike, Suite 600, Falls Church, Virginia 22041 [-END TRANSLATE-](<strong><a href="http://www.iccsafe.org/">www.iccsafe.org</a></strong>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]International Building Code, 2000 Edition (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-207_1" class="navSectionLink">207.1</a>, <a href="#ada-207_2" class="navSectionLink">207.2</a>, <a href="#ada-216_4_2" class="navSectionLink">216.4.2</a>, <a href="#ada-216_4_3" class="navSectionLink">216.4.3</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and [-END TRANSLATE-]1005.2.1).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]International Building Code, 2001 Supplement (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-207_1" class="navSectionLink">207.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and 207.2).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]International Building Code, 2003 Edition (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-207_1" class="navSectionLink">207.1</a>, <a href="#ada-207_2" class="navSectionLink">207.2</a>, <a href="#ada-216_4_2" class="navSectionLink">216.4.2</a>, <a href="#ada-216_4_3" class="navSectionLink">216.4.3</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] 1005.2.1).</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 105.2.4 ICC/IBC.  International Building Code (IBC)-2000 (including 2001 Supplement to the International Codes) and IBC-2003 are referenced for means of egress, areas of refuge, and railings provided on fishing piers and platforms.  At least one accessible means of egress is required for every accessible space and at least two accessible means of egress are required where more than one means of egress is required.  The technical criteria for accessible means of egress allow the use of exit stairways and evacuation elevators when provided in conjunction with horizontal exits or areas of refuge.  While typical elevators are not designed to be used during an emergency evacuation, evacuation elevators are designed with standby power and other features according to the elevator safety standard and can be used for the evacuation of individuals with disabilities.  The IBC also provides requirements for areas of refuge, which are fire-rated spaces on levels above or below the exit discharge levels where people unable to use stairs can go to register a call for assistance and wait for evacuation.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The recreation facilities requirements of this document references two sections in the IBC for fishing piers and platforms.  An exception addresses the height of the railings, guards, or handrails where a fishing pier or platform is required to include a guard, railing, or handrail higher than 34 inches (865 mm) above the ground or deck surface.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-105_2_">105.2.5 NFPA</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Copies of the referenced standards may be obtained from the National Fire Protection Association, 1 Batterymarch Park, Quincy, Massachusetts 02169-7471, [-END TRANSLATE-](<strong><a href="http://www.nfpa.org/">http://www.nfpa.org</a></strong>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]NFPA 72 National Fire Alarm Code, 1999 Edition (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-702_1" class="navSectionLink">702.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_5_2" class="navSectionLink">809.5.2</a>).</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]NFPA 72 National Fire Alarm Code, 2002 Edition (see[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-702_1" class="navSectionLink">702.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_5_2" class="navSectionLink">809.5.2</a>).</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 105.2.5 NFPA.  NFPA 72-1999 and NFPA 72-2002 address the application, installation, performance, and maintenance of protective signaling systems and their components.  The NFPA 72 incorporates Underwriters Laboratory (UL) 1971 by reference.  The standard specifies the characteristics of audible alarms, such as placement and sound levels.  However, Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-702" class="navSectionLink">702</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of these requirements limits the volume of an audible alarm to 110 dBA, rather than the maximum 120 dBA permitted by NFPA 72-1999.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]NFPA 72 specifies characteristics for visible alarms, such as flash frequency, color, intensity, placement, and synchronization.  However, Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-702" class="navSectionLink">702</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of this document requires that visual alarm appliances be permanently installed.  UL 1971 specifies intensity dispersion requirements for visible alarms.  In particular, NFPA 72 requires visible alarms to have a light source that is clear or white and has polar dispersion complying with UL 1971.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h2 id="ada-106">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]106 Definitions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-106_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]106.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]For the purpose of this document, the terms defined in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-106_5" class="navSectionLink">106.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]have the indicated meaning.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 106.1 General.  Terms defined in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-106_5" class="navSectionLink">106.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]are italicized in the text of this document.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h3 id="ada-106_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]106.2 Terms Defined in Referenced Standards[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Terms not defined in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-106_5" class="navSectionLink">106.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or in regulations issued by the Department of Justice and the Department of Transportation to implement the Americans with Disabilities Act, but specifically defined in a referenced standard, shall have the specified meaning from the referenced standard unless otherwise stated.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-106_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]106.3 Undefined Terms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The meaning of terms not specifically defined in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-106_5" class="navSectionLink">106.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or in regulations issued by the Department of Justice and the Department of Transportation to implement the Americans with Disabilities Act or in referenced standards shall be as defined by collegiate dictionaries in the sense that the context implies.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-106_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]106.4 Interchangeability[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Words, terms and phrases used in the singular include the plural and those used in the plural include the singular.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-106_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]106.5 Defined Terms.[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<dl>
<dt class="standards" id="accessible">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Accessible[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A site, building, facility, or portion thereof that complies with this part.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="accessible_means_of_egress">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Accessible Means of Egress[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A continuous and unobstructed way of egress travel from any point in a building or facility that provides an accessible route to an area of refuge, a horizontal exit, or a public way.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="addition">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Addition[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An expansion, extension, or increase in the gross floor area or height of a building or facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="administrative_authority">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Administrative Authority[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A governmental agency that adopts or enforces regulations and guidelines for the design, construction, or alteration of buildings and facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="alteration">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Alteration[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A change to a building or facility that affects or could affect the usability of the building or facility or portion thereof.  Alterations include, but are not limited to, remodeling, renovation, rehabilitation, reconstruction, historic restoration, resurfacing of circulation paths or vehicular ways, changes or rearrangement of the structural parts or elements, and changes or rearrangement in the plan configuration of walls and full-height partitions.  Normal maintenance, reroofing, painting or wallpapering, or changes to mechanical and electrical systems are not alterations unless they affect the usability of the building or facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="amusement_attraction">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Amusement Attraction[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Any facility, or portion of a facility, located within an amusement park or theme park which provides amusement without the use of an amusement device.  Amusement attractions include, but are not limited to, fun houses, barrels, and other attractions without seats.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="amusement_ride">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Amusement Ride[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A system that moves persons through a fixed course within a defined area for the purpose of amusement.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="amusement_ride_seat">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Amusement Ride Seat[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A seat that is built-in or mechanically fastened to an amusement ride intended to be occupied by one or more passengers.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="area_of_sport_activity">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Area of Sport Activity[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]That portion of a room or space where the play or practice of a sport occurs.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="assembly_area">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Assembly Area[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A building or facility, or portion thereof, used for the purpose of entertainment, educational or civic gatherings, or similar purposes.  For the purposes of these requirements, assembly areas include, but are not limited to, classrooms, lecture halls, courtrooms, public meeting rooms, public hearing rooms, legislative chambers, motion picture houses, auditoria, theaters, playhouses, dinner theaters, concert halls, centers for the performing arts, amphitheaters, arenas, stadiums, grandstands, or convention centers.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="assistive_listening_system_(als)">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Assistive Listening System (ALS)[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An amplification system utilizing transmitters, receivers, and coupling devices to bypass the acoustical space between a sound source and a listener by means of induction loop, radio frequency, infrared, or direct-wired equipment.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="boarding_pier">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Boarding Pier[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A portion of a pier where a boat is temporarily secured for the purpose of embarking or disembarking.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="boat_launch_ramp">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Boat Launch Ramp[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A sloped surface designed for launching and retrieving trailered boats and other water craft to and from a body of water.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="boat_slip">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Boat Slip[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]That portion of a pier, main pier, finger pier, or float where a boat is moored for the purpose of berthing, embarking, or disembarking.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="building">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Building[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Any structure used or intended for supporting or sheltering any use or occupancy.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="catch_pool">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Catch Pool[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A pool or designated section of a pool used as a terminus for water slide flumes.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="characters">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Characters[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Letters, numbers, punctuation marks and typographic symbols.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="children’s_use">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Children’s Use[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE]Describes spaces and elements specifically designed for use primarily by people 12 years old and younger.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="circulation_path">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Circulation Path[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An exterior or interior way of passage provided for pedestrian travel, including but not limited to, walks, hallways, courtyards, elevators, platform lifts, ramps, stairways, and landings.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="closed-circuit_telephone">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Closed-Circuit Telephone[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A telephone with a dedicated line such as a house phone, courtesy phone or phone that must be used to gain entry to a facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="common_use">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Common Use[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Interior or exterior circulation paths, rooms, spaces, or elements that are not for public use and are made available for the shared use of two or more people.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="cross_slope">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Cross Slope[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The slope that is perpendicular to the direction of travel (see running slope).[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="curb_ramp">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Curb Ramp[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A short ramp cutting through a curb or built up to it.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="detectable_warning">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Detectable Warning[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A standardized surface feature built in or applied to walking surfaces or other elements to warn of hazards on a circulation path.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="element">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Element[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An architectural or mechanical component of a building, facility, space, or site.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="elevated_play_component">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Elevated Play Component[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A play component that is approached above or below grade and that is part of a composite play structure consisting of two or more play components attached or functionally linked to create an integrated unit providing more than one play activity.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="employee_work_area">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Employee Work Area[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]All or any portion of a space used only by employees and used only for work.  Corridors, toilet rooms, kitchenettes and break rooms are not employee work areas.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="entrance">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Entrance[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Any access point to a building or portion of a building or facility used for the purpose of entering.  An entrance includes the approach walk, the vertical access leading to the entrance platform, the entrance platform itself, vestibule if provided, the entry door or gate, and the hardware of the entry door or gate.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="facility">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Facility[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]All or any portion of buildings, structures, site improvements, elements, and pedestrian routes or vehicular ways located on a site.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="gangway">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Gangway[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A variable-sloped pedestrian walkway that links a fixed structure or land with a floating structure.  Gangways that connect to vessels are not addressed by this document.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="golf_car_passage">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Golf Car Passage[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A continuous passage on which a motorized golf car can operate.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="ground_level_play_component">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Ground Level Play Component[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A play component that is approached and exited at the ground level.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="key_station">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Key Station[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Rapid and light rail stations, and commuter rail stations, as defined under criteria established by the Department of Transportation in 49 CFR 37.47 and 49 CFR 37.51, respectively.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="mail_boxes">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Mail Boxes[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Receptacles for the receipt of documents, packages, or other deliverable matter.  Mail boxes include, but are not limited to, post office boxes and receptacles provided by commercial mail-receiving agencies, apartment facilities, or schools.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="marked_crossing">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Marked Crossing[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A crosswalk or other identified path intended for pedestrian use in crossing a vehicular way.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="mezzanine">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Mezzanine[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An intermediate level or levels between the floor and ceiling of any story with an aggregate floor area of not more than one-third of the area of the room or space in which the level or levels are located.  Mezzanines have sufficient elevation that space for human occupancy can be provided on the floor below.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="occupant_load">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Occupant Load[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The number of persons for which the means of egress of a building or portion of a building is designed.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="operable_part">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Operable Part[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A component of an element used to insert or withdraw objects, or to activate, deactivate, or adjust the element.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="pictogram">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Pictogram[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A pictorial symbol that represents activities, facilities, or concepts.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="play_area">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Play Area[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A portion of a site containing play components designed and constructed for children.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="play_component">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Play Component[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An element intended to generate specific opportunities for play, socialization, or learning.  Play components are manufactured or natural; and are stand-alone or part of a composite play structure.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="private_building_or_facility">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Private Building or Facility[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A place of public accommodation or a commercial building or facility subject to title III of the ADA and 28 CFR part 36 or a transportation building or facility subject to title III of the ADA and 49 CFR 37.45.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="public_building_or_facility">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Public Building or Facility[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A building or facility or portion of a building or facility designed, constructed, or altered by, on behalf of, or for the use of a public entity subject to title II of the ADA and 28 CFR part 35 or to title II of the ADA and 49 CFR 37.41 or 37.43.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="public_entrance">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Public Entrance[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An entrance that is not a service entrance or a restricted entrance.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="public_use">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Public Use[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Interior or exterior rooms, spaces, or elements that are made available to the public. Public use may be provided at a building or facility that is privately or publicly owned.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="public_way">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Public Way[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Any street, alley or other parcel of land open to the outside air leading to a public street, which has been deeded, dedicated or otherwise permanently appropriated to the public for public use and which has a clear width and height of not less than 10 feet (3050 mm).[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="qualified_historic_building_or_facility">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Qualified Historic Building or Facility[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A building or facility that is listed in or eligible for listing in the National Register of Historic Places, or designated as historic under an appropriate State or local law.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="ramp">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Ramp[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A walking surface that has a running slope steeper than 1:20.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="residential_dwelling_unit">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Residential Dwelling Unit[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A unit intended to be used as a residence, that is primarily long-term in nature.  Residential dwelling units do not include transient lodging, inpatient medical care, licensed long-term care, and detention or correctional facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="restricted_entrance">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Restricted Entrance[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An entrance that is made available for common use on a controlled basis but not public use and that is not a service entrance.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="running_slope">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Running Slope[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The slope that is parallel to the direction of travel (see cross slope).[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="self-service_storage">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Self-Service Storage[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Building or facility designed and used for the purpose of renting or leasing individual storage spaces to customers for the purpose of storing and removing personal property on a self-service basis.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="service_entrance">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Service Entrance[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An entrance intended primarily for delivery of goods or services.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="site">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Site[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A parcel of land bounded by a property line or a designated portion of a public right-of-way.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="soft_contained_play_structure">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Soft Contained Play Structure[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A play structure made up of one or more play components where the user enters a fully enclosed play environment that utilizes pliable materials, such as plastic, netting, or fabric.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="space">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Space[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A definable area, such as a room, toilet room, hall, assembly area, entrance, storage room, alcove, courtyard, or lobby.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="story">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Story[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]That portion of a building or facility designed for human occupancy included between the upper surface of a floor and upper surface of the floor or roof next above.  A story containing one or more mezzanines has more than one floor level.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="structural_frame">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Structural Frame[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The columns and the girders, beams, and trusses having direct connections to the columns and all other members that are essential to the stability of the building or facility as a whole.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="tactile">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Tactile[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An object that can be perceived using the sense of touch.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="technically_infeasible">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Technically Infeasible[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]With respect to an alteration of a building or a facility, something that has little likelihood of being accomplished because existing structural conditions would require removing or altering a load-bearing member that is an essential part of the structural frame; or because other existing physical or site constraints prohibit modification or addition of elements, spaces, or features that are in full and strict compliance with the minimum requirements.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="teeing_ground">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Teeing Ground[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In golf, the starting place for the hole to be played.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="transfer_device">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Transfer Device[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Equipment designed to facilitate the transfer of a person from a wheelchair or other mobility aid to and from an amusement ride seat.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="transient_lodging">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Transient Lodging[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A building or facility containing one or more guest room(s) for sleeping that provides accommodations that are primarily short-term in nature.  Transient lodging does not include residential dwelling units intended to be used as a residence, inpatient medical care facilities, licensed long-term care facilities, detention or correctional facilities, or private buildings or facilities that contain not more than five rooms for rent or hire and that are actually occupied by the proprietor as the residence of such proprietor.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="transition_plate">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Transition Plate[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A sloping pedestrian walking surface located at the end(s) of a gangway.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="tty">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]TTY[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An abbreviation for teletypewriter.  Machinery that employs interactive text-based communication through the transmission of coded signals across the telephone network. TTYs may include, for example, devices known as TDDs (telecommunication display devices or telecommunication devices for deaf persons) or computers with special modems.  TTYs are also called text telephones.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="use_zone">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Use Zone[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The ground level area beneath and immediately adjacent to a play structure or play equipment that is designated by ASTM F 1487 (incorporated by reference, see “Referenced Standards” in Chapter 1) for unrestricted circulation around the play equipment and where it is predicted that a user would land when falling from or exiting the play equipment.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="vehicular_way">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Vehicular Way[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]A route provided for vehicular traffic, such as in a street, driveway, or parking facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="walk">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Walk[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An exterior prepared surface for pedestrian use, including pedestrian areas such as plazas and courts.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="wheelchair_space">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Wheelchair Space[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Space for a single wheelchair and its occupant.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
<dt class="standards" id="work_area_equipment">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Work Area Equipment[-END TRANSLATE-]</dt> <dd>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Any machine, instrument, engine, motor, pump, conveyor, or other apparatus used to perform work.  As used in this document, this term shall apply only to equipment that is permanently installed or built-in in employee work areas.  Work area equipment does not include passenger elevators and other accessible means of vertical transportation.[-END TRANSLATE-]</dd>
    </dl>
<h1></h1> <!--empty last heading for kms load function to work-->
</div>  <!--close #adaCh1-->
<div id="adaCh2">
    <h1 id="a2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Chapter 2: Scoping Requirements[-END TRANSLATE-]</h1>
<h2 id="ada-201">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]201 Application[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-201_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]201.1 Scope[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]All areas of newly designed and newly constructed buildings and facilities and altered portions of existing buildings and facilities shall comply with these requirements.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 201.1 Scope.  These requirements are to be applied to all areas of a facility unless exempted, or where scoping limits the number of multiple elements required to be accessible.  For example, not all medical care patient rooms are required to be accessible; those that are not required to be accessible are not required to comply with these requirements.  However, common use and public use spaces such as recovery rooms, examination rooms, and cafeterias are not exempt from these requirements and must be accessible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-201_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]201.2 Application Based on Building or Facility Use[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where a site, building, facility, room, or space contains more than one use, each portion shall comply with the applicable requirements for that use.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-201_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]201.3 Temporary and Permanent Structures[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]These requirements shall apply to temporary and permanent buildings and facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 201.3 Temporary and Permanent Structures.  Temporary buildings or facilities covered by these requirements include, but are not limited to, reviewing stands, temporary classrooms, bleacher areas, stages, platforms and daises, fixed furniture systems, wall systems, and exhibit areas, temporary banking facilities, and temporary health screening facilities.  Structures and equipment directly associated with the actual processes of construction are not required to be accessible as permitted in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-203_2" class="navSectionLink">203.2</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-202">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202 Existing Buildings and Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-202_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Additions and alterations to existing buildings or facilities shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202" class="navSectionLink">202</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-202_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.2 Additions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Each addition to an existing building or facility shall comply with the requirements for new construction.  Each addition that affects or could affect the usability of or access to an area containing a primary function shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_4" class="navSectionLink">202.4</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-202_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.3 Alterations[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where existing elements or spaces are altered, each altered element or space shall comply with the applicable requirements of Chapter 2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-202_3x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Unless required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_4" class="navSectionLink">202.4</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]where elements or spaces are altered and the circulation path to the altered element or space is not altered, an accessible route shall not be required.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-202_3x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  In alterations, where compliance with applicable requirements is technically infeasible, the alteration shall comply with the requirements to the maximum extent feasible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-202_3x3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  Residential dwelling units not required to be accessible in compliance with a standard issued pursuant to the Americans with Disabilities Act or Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as amended, shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_3" class="navSectionLink">202.3</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 202.3 Alterations.  Although covered entities are permitted to limit the scope of an alteration to individual elements, the alteration of multiple elements within a room or space may provide a cost-effective opportunity to make the entire room or space accessible.  Any elements or spaces of the building or facility that are required to comply with these requirements must be made accessible within the scope of the alteration, to the maximum extent feasible.  If providing accessibility in compliance with these requirements for people with one type of disability (e.g., people who use wheelchairs) is not feasible, accessibility must still be provided in compliance with the requirements for people with other types of disabilities (e.g., people who have hearing impairments or who have vision impairments) to the extent that such accessibility is feasible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-202_3_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.3.1 Prohibited Reduction in Access[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An alteration that decreases or has the effect of decreasing the accessibility of a building or facility below the requirements for new construction at the time of the alteration is prohibited.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-202_3_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.3.2 Extent of Application[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]An alteration of an existing element, space, or area of a building or facility shall not impose a requirement for accessibility greater than required for new construction.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-202_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.4 Alterations Affecting Primary Function Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In addition to the requirements of[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_3" class="navSectionLink">202.3</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]an alteration that affects or could affect the usability of or access to an area containing a primary function shall be made so as to ensure that, to the maximum extent feasible, the path of travel to the altered area, including the rest rooms, telephones, and drinking fountains serving the altered area, are readily accessible to and usable by individuals with disabilities, unless such alterations are disproportionate to the overall alterations in terms of cost and scope as determined under criteria established by the Attorney General.  In existing transportation facilities, an area of primary function shall be as defined under regulations published by the Secretary of the Department of Transportation or the Attorney General.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Residential dwelling units shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_4" class="navSectionLink">202.4</a>.</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 202.4 Alterations Affecting Primary Function Areas.  An area of a building or facility containing a major activity for which the building or facility is intended is a primary function area.  Department of Justice ADA regulations state, “Alterations made to provide an accessible path of travel to the altered area will be deemed disproportionate to the overall alteration when the cost exceeds 20% of the cost of the alteration to the primary function area.”  (28 CFR 36.403 (f)(1)). See also Department of Transportation ADA regulations, which use similar concepts in the context of public sector transportation facilities (49 CFR 37.43 (e)(1)).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]There can be multiple areas containing a primary function in a single building.  Primary function areas are not limited to public use areas.  For example, both a bank lobby and the bank’s employee areas such as the teller areas and walk-in safe are primary function areas.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Also, mixed use facilities may include numerous primary function areas for each use. Areas containing a primary function do not include: mechanical rooms, boiler rooms, supply storage rooms, employee lounges or locker rooms, janitorial closets, entrances, corridors, or restrooms.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h3 id="ada-202_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]202.5 Alterations to Qualified Historic Buildings and Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Alterations to a qualified historic building or facility shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_3" class="navSectionLink">202.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_4" class="navSectionLink">202.4</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Where the State Historic Preservation Officer or Advisory Council on Historic Preservation determines that compliance with the requirements for accessible routes, entrances, or toilet facilities would threaten or destroy the historic significance of the building or facility, the exceptions for alterations to qualified historic buildings or facilities for that element shall be permitted to apply.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 202.5 Alterations to Qualified Historic Buildings and Facilities Exception.  State Historic Preservation Officers are State appointed officials who carry out certain responsibilities under the National Historic Preservation Act.  State Historic Preservation Officers consult with Federal and State agencies, local governments, and private entities on providing access and protecting significant elements of qualified historic buildings and facilities. There are exceptions for alterations to qualified historic buildings and facilities for accessible routes (206.2.1 Exception 1 and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Exception 7); entrances (206.4 Exception 2); and toilet facilities (213.2 Exception 2).  When an entity believes that compliance with the requirements for any of these elements would threaten or destroy the historic significance of the building or facility, the entity should consult with the State Historic Preservation Officer.  If the State Historic Preservation Officer agrees that compliance with the requirements for a specific element would threaten or destroy the historic significance of the building or facility, use of the exception is permitted.  Public entities have an additional obligation to achieve program accessibility under the Department of Justice ADA regulations.  See 28 CFR 35.150.  These regulations require public entities that operate historic preservation programs to give priority to methods that provide physical access to individuals with disabilities.  If alterations to a qualified historic building or facility to achieve program accessibility would threaten or destroy the historic significance of the building or facility, fundamentally alter the program, or result in undue financial or administrative burdens, the Department of Justice ADA regulations allow alternative methods to be used to achieve program accessibility.  In the case of historic preservation programs, such as an historic house museum, alternative methods include using audio-visual materials to depict portions of the house that cannot otherwise be made accessible.  In the case of other qualified historic properties, such as an historic government office building, alternative methods include relocating programs and services to accessible locations.  The Department of Justice ADA regulations also allow public entities to use alternative methods when altering qualified historic buildings or facilities in the rare situations where the State Historic Preservation Officer determines that it is not feasible to provide physical access using the exceptions permitted in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_5" class="navSectionLink">202.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]without threatening or destroying the historic significance of the building or facility.  See 28 CFR 35.151(d).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The AccessAbility Office at the National Endowment for the Arts (NEA) provides a variety of resources for museum operators and historic properties including:  the Design for Accessibility Guide and the Disability Symbols.  Contact NEA about these and other resources at 202-682-5532 or[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="http://www.arts.gov">www.arts.gov</a>.</p>
</div>
<h2 id="ada-203">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203 General Exceptions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-203_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Sites, buildings, facilities, and elements are exempt from these requirements to the extent specified by 203.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.2 Construction Sites[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Structures and sites directly associated with the actual processes of construction, including but not limited to, scaffolding, bridging, materials hoists, materials storage, and construction trailers shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.  Portable toilet units provided for use exclusively by construction personnel on a construction site shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-213" class="navSectionLink">213</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.3 Raised Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Areas raised primarily for purposes of security, life safety, or fire safety, including but not limited to, observation or lookout galleries, prison guard towers, fire towers, or life guard stands shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.4 Limited Access Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Spaces accessed only by ladders, catwalks, crawl spaces, or very narrow passageways shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.5 Machinery Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Spaces frequented only by service personnel for maintenance, repair, or occasional monitoring of equipment shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.  Machinery spaces include, but are not limited to, elevator pits or elevator penthouses; mechanical, electrical or communications equipment rooms; piping or equipment catwalks; water or sewage treatment pump rooms and stations; electric substations and transformer vaults; and highway and tunnel utility facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.6 Single Occupant Structures[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Single occupant structures accessed only by passageways below grade or elevated above standard curb height, including but not limited to, toll booths that are accessed only by underground tunnels, shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.7 Detention and Correctional Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In detention and correctional facilities, common use areas that are used only by inmates or detainees and security personnel and that do not serve holding cells or housing cells required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-232" class="navSectionLink">232</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_8">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.8 Residential Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In residential facilities, common use areas that do not serve residential dwelling units required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_9">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.9 Employee Work Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Spaces and elements within employee work areas shall only be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_8" class="navSectionLink">206.2.8</a>, <a href="#ada-207_1" class="navSectionLink">207.1</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-215_3" class="navSectionLink">215.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and shall be designed and constructed so that individuals with disabilities can approach, enter, and exit the employee work area.  Employee work areas, or portions of employee work areas, other than raised courtroom stations, that are less than 300 square feet (28 m2) and elevated 7 inches (180 mm) or more above the finish floor or ground where the elevation is essential to the function of the space shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 203.9 Employee Work Areas.  Although areas used exclusively by employees for work are not required to be fully accessible, consider designing such areas to include non-required turning spaces, and provide accessible elements whenever possible.  Under the ADA, employees with disabilities are entitled to reasonable accommodations in the workplace; accommodations can include alterations to spaces within the facility.  Designing employee work areas to be more accessible at the outset will avoid more costly retrofits when current employees become temporarily or permanently disabled, or when new employees with disabilities are hired.  Contact the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) at[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="http://www.eeoc.gov">www.eeoc.gov</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]for information about title I of the ADA prohibiting discrimination against people with disabilities in the workplace.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_10">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.10 Raised Refereeing, Judging, and Scoring Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Raised structures used solely for refereeing, judging, or scoring a sport shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_11">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.11 Water Slides[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Water slides shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_12">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.12 Animal Containment Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Animal containment areas that are not for public use shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 203.12 Animal Containment Areas.  Public circulation routes where animals may travel, such as in petting zoos and passageways alongside animal pens in State fairs, are not eligible for the exception.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_13">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.13 Raised Boxing or Wrestling Rings[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Raised boxing or wrestling rings shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-203_14">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]203.14 Raised Diving Boards and Diving Platforms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Raised diving boards and diving platforms shall not be required to comply with these requirements or to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-204">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]204 Protruding Objects[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-204_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]204.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Protruding objects on circulation paths shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-307" class="navSectionLink">307</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-204_1x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Within areas of sport activity, protruding objects on circulation paths shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-307" class="navSectionLink">307</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-204_1x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Within play areas, protruding objects on circulation paths shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-307" class="navSectionLink">307</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]provided that ground level accessible routes provide vertical clearance in compliance with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1008_2" class="navSectionLink">1008.2</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-205">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]205 Operable Parts[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-205_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]205.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Operable parts on accessible elements, accessible routes, and in accessible rooms and spaces shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Operable parts that are intended for use only by service or maintenance personnel shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Electrical or communication receptacles serving a dedicated use shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  Where two or more outlets are provided in a kitchen above a length of counter top that is uninterrupted by a sink or appliance, one outlet shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]4.  Floor electrical receptacles shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]5.  HVAC diffusers shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]6.  Except for light switches, where redundant controls are provided for a single element, one control in each space shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]7.  Cleats and other boat securement devices shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309_3" class="navSectionLink">309.3</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-205_1x8">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]8.  Exercise machines and exercise equipment shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 205.1 General.  Controls covered by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-205_1" class="navSectionLink">205.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]include, but are not limited to, light switches, circuit breakers, duplexes and other convenience receptacles, environmental and appliance controls, plumbing fixture controls, and security and intercom systems.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-206">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206 Accessible Routes[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-206_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Accessible routes shall be provided in accordance with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206" class="navSectionLink">206</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and shall comply with Chapter 4.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2 Where Required[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Accessible routes shall be provided where required by 206.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.1 Site Arrival Points[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible route shall be provided within the site from accessible parking spaces and accessible passenger loading zones; public streets and sidewalks; and public transportation stops to the accessible building or facility entrance they serve.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_1x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Where exceptions for alterations to qualified historic buildings or facilities are permitted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_5" class="navSectionLink">202.5</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]no more than one accessible route from a site arrival point to an accessible entrance shall be required.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_1x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  An accessible route shall not be required between site arrival points and the building or facility entrance if the only means of access between them is a vehicular way not providing pedestrian access.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.1 Site Arrival Points.  Each site arrival point must be connected by an accessible route to the accessible building entrance or entrances served.  Where two or more similar site arrival points, such as bus stops, serve the same accessible entrance or entrances, both bus stops must be on accessible routes.  In addition, the accessible routes must serve all of the accessible entrances on the site.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.1 Site Arrival Points Exception 2.  Access from site arrival points may include vehicular ways.  Where a vehicular way, or a portion of a vehicular way, is provided for pedestrian travel, such as within a shopping center or shopping mall parking lot, this exception does not apply.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.2 Within a Site[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible route shall connect accessible buildings, accessible facilities, accessible elements, and accessible spaces that are on the same site.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_2x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  An accessible route shall not be required between accessible buildings, accessible facilities, accessible elements, and accessible spaces if the only means of access between them is a vehicular way not providing pedestrian access.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.2 Within a Site.  An accessible route is required to connect to the boundary of each area of sport activity. Examples of areas of sport activity include: soccer fields, basketball courts, baseball fields, running tracks, skating rinks, and the area surrounding a piece of gymnastic equipment.  While the size of an area of sport activity may vary from sport to sport, each includes only the space needed to play.  Where multiple sports fields or courts are provided, an accessible route is required to each field or area of sport activity.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.3 Multi-Story Buildings and Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible route shall connect each story and mezzanine in multi-story buildings and facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  In private buildings or facilities that are less than three stories or that have less than 3000 square feet (279 m2) per story, an accessible route shall not be required to connect stories provided that the building or facility is not a shopping center, a shopping mall, the professional office of a health care provider, a terminal, depot or other station used for specified public transportation, an airport passenger terminal, or another type of facility as determined by the Attorney General.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Where a two story public building or facility has one story with an occupant load of five or fewer persons that does not contain public use space, that story shall not be required to be connected to the story above or below.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  In detention and correctional facilities, an accessible route shall not be required to connect stories where cells with mobility features required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]all common use areas serving cells with mobility features required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and all public use areas are on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]4.  In residential facilities, an accessible route shall not be required to connect stories where residential dwelling units with mobility features required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]all common use areas serving residential dwelling units with mobility features required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and public use areas serving residential dwelling units are on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]5.  Within multi-story transient lodging guest rooms with mobility features required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806_2" class="navSectionLink">806.2</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]an accessible route shall not be required to connect stories provided that spaces complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806_2" class="navSectionLink">806.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]are on an accessible route and sleeping accommodations for two persons minimum are provided on a story served by an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]6.  In air traffic control towers, an accessible route shall not be required to serve the cab and the floor immediately below the cab.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_3x7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]7.  Where exceptions for alterations to qualified historic buildings or facilities are permitted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_5" class="navSectionLink">202.5</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]an accessible route shall not be required to stories located above or below the accessible story.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.3 Multi-Story Buildings and Facilities.  Spaces and elements located on a level not required to be served by an accessible route must fully comply with this document.  While a mezzanine may be a change in level, it is not a story.  If an accessible route is required to connect stories within a building or facility, the accessible route must serve all mezzanines.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.3 Multi-Story Buildings and Facilities Exception 4.  Where common use areas are provided for the use of residents, it is presumed that all such common use areas “serve” accessible dwelling units unless use is restricted to residents occupying certain dwelling units.  For example, if all residents are permitted to use all laundry rooms, then all laundry rooms “serve” accessible dwelling units.  However, if the laundry room on the first floor is restricted to use by residents on the first floor, and the second floor laundry room is for use by occupants of the second floor, then first floor accessible units are “served” only by laundry rooms on the first floor.  In this example, an accessible route is not required to the second floor provided that all accessible units and all common use areas serving them are on the first floor.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h5 id="ada-206_2_3_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.3.1 Stairs and Escalators in Existing Buildings[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In alterations and additions, where an escalator or stair is provided where none existed previously and major structural modifications are necessary for the installation, an accessible route shall be provided between the levels served by the escalator or stair unless exempted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Exceptions 1 through 7.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.4 Spaces and Elements[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible route shall connect accessible building or facility entrances with all accessible spaces and elements within the building or facility which are otherwise connected by a circulation path unless exempted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Exceptions 1 through 7.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_4x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Raised courtroom stations, including judges’ benches, clerks’ stations, bailiffs’ stations, deputy clerks’ stations, and court reporters’ stations shall not be required to provide vertical access provided that the required clear floor space, maneuvering space, and, if appropriate, electrical service are installed at the time of initial construction to allow future installation of a means of vertical access complying with [-END TRANSLATE-]<a href="#ada-405" class="navSectionLink">405</a>, <a href="#ada-407" class="navSectionLink">407</a>, <a href="#ada-408" class="navSectionLink">408</a>,[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-] or [-END TRANSLATE-]<a href="#ada-410" class="navSectionLink">410</a>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-] without requiring substantial reconstruction of the space.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_4x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  In assembly areas with fixed seating required to comply with [-END TRANSLATE-]<a href="#ada-221" class="navSectionLink">221</a>,[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-] an accessible route shall not be required to serve fixed seating where wheelchair spaces required to be on an accessible route are not provided.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_4x3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  Accessible routes shall not be required to connect mezzanines where buildings or facilities have no more than one story.  In addition, accessible routes shall not be required to connect stories or mezzanines where multi-story buildings or facilities are exempted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Exceptions 1 through 7.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.4 Spaces and Elements.  accessible routes must connect all spaces and elements required to be accessible including, but not limited to, raised areas and speaker platforms.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.4 Spaces and Elements Exception 1.  The exception does not apply to areas that are likely to be used by members of the public who are not employees of the court such as jury areas, attorney areas, or witness stands.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.5 Restaurants and Cafeterias[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In restaurants and cafeterias, an accessible route shall be provided to all dining areas, including raised or sunken dining areas, and outdoor dining areas.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_5x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  In buildings or facilities not required to provide an accessible route between stories, an accessible route shall not be required to a mezzanine dining area where the mezzanine contains less than 25 percent of the total combined area for seating and dining and where the same decor and services are provided in the accessible area.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_5x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  In alterations, an accessible route shall not be required to existing raised or sunken dining areas, or to all parts of existing outdoor dining areas where the same services and decor are provided in an accessible space usable by the public and not restricted to use by people with disabilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_5x3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  In sports facilities, tiered dining areas providing seating required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-221" class="navSectionLink">221</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be required to have accessible routes serving at least 25 percent of the dining area provided that accessible routes serve seating complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-221" class="navSectionLink">221</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and each tier is provided with the same services.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.5 Restaurants and Cafeterias Exception 2.  Examples of “same services” include, but are not limited to, bar service, rooms having smoking and non-smoking sections, lotto and other table games, carry-out, and buffet service.  Examples of “same decor” include, but are not limited to, seating at or near windows and railings with views, areas designed with a certain theme, party and banquet rooms, and rooms where entertainment is provided.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.6 Performance Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where a circulation path directly connects a performance area to an assembly seating area, an accessible route shall directly connect the assembly seating area with the performance area.  An accessible route shall be provided from performance areas to ancillary areas or facilities used by performers unless exempted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]exceptions 1 through 7.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.7 Press Boxes[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Press boxes in assembly areas shall be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_7x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  An accessible route shall not be required to press boxes in bleachers that have points of entry at only one level provided that the aggregate area of all press boxes is 500 square feet (46 m2) maximum.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_7x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  An accessible route shall not be required to free-standing press boxes that are elevated above grade 12 feet (3660 mm) minimum provided that the aggregate area of all press boxes is 500 square feet (46 m2) maximum.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.7 Press Boxes Exception 2.  Where a facility contains multiple assembly areas, the aggregate area of the press boxes in each assembly area is to be calculated separately.  For example, if a university has a soccer stadium with three press boxes elevated 12 feet (3660 mm) or more above grade and each press box is 150 square feet (14 m2), then the aggregate area of the soccer stadium press boxes is less than 500 square feet (46 m2) and Exception 2 applies to the soccer stadium.  If that same university also has a football stadium with two press boxes elevated 12 feet (3660 mm) or more above grade and one press box is 250 square feet (23 m2), and the second is 275 square feet (26 m2), then the aggregate area of the football stadium press boxes is more than 500 square feet (46 m2) and Exception 2 does not apply to the football stadium.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_8">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.8 Employee Work Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Common use circulation paths within employee work areas shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-402" class="navSectionLink">402</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_8x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Common use circulation paths located within employee work areas that are less than 1000 square feet (93 m2) and defined by permanently installed partitions, counters, casework, or furnishings shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-402" class="navSectionLink">402</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_8x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Common use circulation paths located within employee work areas that are an integral component of work area equipment shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-402" class="navSectionLink">402</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_2_8x3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  Common use circulation paths located within exterior employee work areas that are fully exposed to the weather shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-402" class="navSectionLink">402</a>.</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.8 Employee Work Areas Exception 1.  Modular furniture that is not permanently installed is not directly subject to these requirements.  The Department of Justice ADA regulations provide additional guidance regarding the relationship between these requirements and elements that are not part of the built environment.  Additionally, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) implements title I of the ADA which requires non-discrimination in the workplace.  EEOC can provide guidance regarding employers’ obligations to provide reasonable accommodations for employees with disabilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.2.8 Employee Work Areas Exception 2.  Large pieces of equipment, such as electric turbines or water pumping apparatus, may have stairs and elevated walkways used for overseeing or monitoring purposes which are physically part of the turbine or pump.  However, passenger elevators used for vertical transportation between stories are not considered “work area equipment” as defined in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-106_5" class="navSectionLink">106.5</a>.</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_9">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.9 Amusement Rides[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Amusement rides required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-234" class="navSectionLink">234</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall provide accessible routes in accordance with 206.2.9.  accessible routes serving amusement rides shall comply with Chapter 4 except as modified by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_2" class="navSectionLink">1002.2</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_2_9_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.9.1 Load and Unload Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Load and unload areas shall be on an accessible route.  Where load and unload areas have more than one loading or unloading position, at least one loading and unloading position shall be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_2_9_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.9.2 Wheelchair Spaces, Ride Seats Designed for Transfer, and Transfer Devices[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]When amusement rides are in the load and unload position, wheelchair spaces complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_4" class="navSectionLink">1002.4</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]amusement ride seats designed for transfer complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_5" class="navSectionLink">1002.5</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and transfer devices complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_6" class="navSectionLink">1002.6</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_10">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.10 Recreational Boating Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Boat slips required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-235_2" class="navSectionLink">235.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and boarding piers at boat launch ramps required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-235_3" class="navSectionLink">235.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be on an accessible route.  accessible routes serving recreational boating facilities shall comply with Chapter 4, except as modified by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1003_2" class="navSectionLink">1003.2</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_11">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.11 Bowling Lanes[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where bowling lanes are provided, at least 5 percent, but no fewer than one of each type of bowling lane, shall be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_12">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.12 Court Sports[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In court sports, at least one accessible route shall directly connect both sides of the court.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_13">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.13 Exercise Machines and Equipment[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Exercise machines and equipment required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-236" class="navSectionLink">236</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_14">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.14 Fishing Piers and Platforms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Fishing piers and platforms shall be on an accessible route.  accessible routes serving fishing piers and platforms shall comply with Chapter 4 except as modified by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1005_1" class="navSectionLink">1005.1</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_15">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.15 Golf Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible route shall connect accessible elements and spaces within the boundary of the golf course.  In addition, accessible routes serving golf car rental areas; bag drop areas; course weather shelters complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-238_2_3" class="navSectionLink">238.2.3</a>; [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-] course toilet rooms; and practice putting greens, practice teeing grounds, and teeing stations at driving ranges complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-238_3" class="navSectionLink">238.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall comply with Chapter 4 except as modified by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1006_2" class="navSectionLink">1006.2</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Golf car passages complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1006_3" class="navSectionLink">1006.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be permitted to be used for all or part of accessible routes required by 206.2.15.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_16">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.16 Miniature Golf Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Holes required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-239_2" class="navSectionLink">239.2</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]including the start of play, shall be on an accessible route.  accessible routes serving miniature golf facilities shall comply with Chapter 4 except as modified by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1007_2" class="navSectionLink">1007.2</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_2_17">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.17 Play Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Play areas shall provide accessible routes in accordance with 206.2.17.  accessible routes serving play areas shall comply with Chapter 4 except as modified by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1008_2" class="navSectionLink">1008.2</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_2_17_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.17.1 Ground Level and Elevated Play Components[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible route shall be provided within the play area.  The accessible route shall connect ground level play components required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240_2_1" class="navSectionLink">240.2.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and elevated play components required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240_2_2" class="navSectionLink">240.2.2</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]including entry and exit points of the play components.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_2_17_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.2.17.2 Soft Contained Play Structures[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where three or fewer entry points are provided for soft contained play structures, at least one entry point shall be on an accessible route.  Where four or more entry points are provided for soft contained play structures, at least two entry points shall be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.3 Location[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Accessible routes shall coincide with or be located in the same area as general circulation paths.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where circulation paths are interior, required accessible routes shall also be interior.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<table role="presentation"  class="standards" style="width: 100%; background-color: #eeeeee; border: 1px solid #000000;">
<tr>
<td>
<p class="standards"><em>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Note to Reader:[-END TRANSLATE-]</em>&nbsp; [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The Department of Transportation’s ADA standards include additional requirements for the location of accessible routes:[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards"><strong>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.3 Location.[-END TRANSLATE-]</strong>&nbsp; [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Accessible routes shall coincide with, or be located in the same area as general circulation paths.  Where circulation paths are interior, required accessible routes shall also be interior. [-END TRANSLATE-]<em>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Elements such as ramps, elevators, or other circulation devices, fare vending or other ticketing areas, and fare collection areas shall be placed to minimize the distance which wheelchair users and other persons who cannot negotiate steps may have to travel compared to the general public.[-END TRANSLATE-]</em></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.3 Location.  The accessible route must be in the same area as the general circulation path.  This means that circulation paths, such as vehicular ways designed for pedestrian traffic, walks, and unpaved paths that are designed to be routinely used by pedestrians must be accessible or have an accessible route nearby.  Additionally, accessible vertical interior circulation must be in the same area as stairs and escalators, not isolated in the back of the facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4 Entrances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Entrances shall be provided in accordance with 206.4.  Entrance doors, doorways, and gates shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and shall be on an accessible route complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-402" class="navSectionLink">402</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_4x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Where an alteration includes alterations to an entrance, and the building or facility has another entrance complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]that is on an accessible route, the altered entrance shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4" class="navSectionLink">206.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]unless required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_4" class="navSectionLink">202.4</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_4x2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Where exceptions for alterations to qualified historic buildings or facilities are permitted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_5" class="navSectionLink">202.5</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]no more than one public entrance shall be required to comply with 206.4.  Where no public entrance can comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4" class="navSectionLink">206.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]under criteria established in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_5" class="navSectionLink">202.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Exception, then either an unlocked entrance not used by the public shall comply with 206.4; or a locked entrance complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4" class="navSectionLink">206.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]with a notification system or remote monitoring shall be provided.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.1 Public Entrances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In addition to entrances required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_2" class="navSectionLink">206.4.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_9" class="navSectionLink">206.4.9</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]at least 60 percent of all public entrances shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.2 Parking Structure Entrances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where direct access is provided for pedestrians from a parking structure to a building or facility entrance, each direct access to the building or facility entrance shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.3 Entrances from Tunnels or Elevated Walkways[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where direct access is provided for pedestrians from a pedestrian tunnel or elevated walkway to a building or facility, at least one direct entrance to the building or facility from each tunnel or walkway shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.4 Transportation Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In addition to the requirements of[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_2" class="navSectionLink">206.4.2</a>, <a href="#ada-206_4_3" class="navSectionLink">206.4.3</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_5" class="navSectionLink">206.4.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_9" class="navSectionLink">206.4.9</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]transportation facilities shall provide entrances in accordance with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_4" class="navSectionLink">206.4.4</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_4_4_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.4.1 Location[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In transportation facilities, where different entrances serve different transportation fixed routes or groups of fixed routes, at least one public entrance serving each fixed route or group of fixed routes shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Entrances to key stations and existing intercity rail stations retrofitted in accordance with 49 CFR 37.49 or 49 CFR 37.51 shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4_4_1" class="navSectionLink">206.4.4.1</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_4_4_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.4.2 Direct Connections[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Direct connections to other facilities shall provide an accessible route complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]from the point of connection to boarding platforms and all transportation system elements required to be accessible.  Any elements provided to facilitate future direct connections shall be on an accessible route connecting boarding platforms and all transportation system elements required to be accessible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  In key stations and existing intercity rail stations, existing direct connections shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-206_4_4_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.4.3 Key Stations and Intercity Rail Stations[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Key stations and existing intercity rail stations required by Subpart C of 49 CFR part 37 to be altered, shall have at least one entrance complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.5 Tenant Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one accessible entrance to each tenancy in a facility shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION: Self-service storage facilities not required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-225_3" class="navSectionLink">225.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to be on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.6 Residential Dwelling Unit Primary Entrance[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In residential dwelling units, at least one primary entrance shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The primary entrance to a residential dwelling unit shall not be to a bedroom.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.7 Restricted Entrances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where restricted entrances are provided to a building or facility, at least one restricted entrance to the building or facility shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_8">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.8 Service Entrances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]If a service entrance is the only entrance to a building or to a tenancy in a facility, that entrance shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_4_9">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.4.9 Entrances for Inmates or Detainees[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where entrances used only by inmates or detainees and security personnel are provided at judicial facilities, detention facilities, or correctional facilities, at least one such entrance shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.5 Doors, Doorways, and Gates[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Doors, doorways, and gates providing user passage shall be provided in accordance with 206.5.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_5_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.5.1 Entrances[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Each entrance to a building or facility required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_4" class="navSectionLink">206.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall have at least one door, doorway, or gate complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_5_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.5.2 Rooms and Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Within a building or facility, at least one door, doorway, or gate serving each room or space complying with these requirements shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_5_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.5.3 Transient Lodging Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In transient lodging facilities, entrances, doors, and doorways providing user passage into and within guest rooms that are not required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806_2" class="navSectionLink">806.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404_2_3" class="navSectionLink">404.2.3</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Shower and sauna doors in guest rooms that are not required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806_2" class="navSectionLink">806.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404_2_3" class="navSectionLink">404.2.3</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_5_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.5.4 Residential Dwelling Units[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In residential dwelling units required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]all doors and doorways providing user passage shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-404" class="navSectionLink">404</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.6 Elevators[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Elevators provided for passengers shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-407" class="navSectionLink">407</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where multiple elevators are provided, each elevator shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-407" class="navSectionLink">407</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_6x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  In a building or facility permitted to use the exceptions to[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or permitted by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_7" class="navSectionLink">206.7</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]to use a platform lift, elevators complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-408" class="navSectionLink">408</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be permitted.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-206_6x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Elevators complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-408" class="navSectionLink">408</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-409" class="navSectionLink">409</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be permitted in multi-story residential dwelling units.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_6_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.6.1 Existing Elevators[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where elements of existing elevators are altered, the same element shall also be altered in all elevators that are programmed to respond to the same hall call control as the altered elevator and shall comply with the requirements of[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-407" class="navSectionLink">407</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]for the altered element.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7 Platform Lifts[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-410" class="navSectionLink">410</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted as a component of an accessible route in new construction in accordance with 206.7.  Platform lifts shall be permitted as a component of an accessible route in an existing building or facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.1 Performance Areas and Speakers’ Platforms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide accessible routes to performance areas and speakers’ platforms.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.2 Wheelchair Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide an accessible route to comply with the wheelchair space dispersion and line-of-sight requirements of[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-221" class="navSectionLink">221</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-802" class="navSectionLink">802</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.3 Incidental Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide an accessible route to incidental spaces which are not public use spaces and which are occupied by five persons maximum.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.4 Judicial Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide an accessible route to: jury boxes and witness stands; raised courtroom stations including, judges’ benches, clerks’ stations, bailiffs’ stations, deputy clerks’ stations, and court reporters’ stations; and to depressed areas such as the well of a court.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.5 Existing Site Constraints[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted where existing exterior site constraints make use of a ramp or elevator infeasible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.7.5 Existing Site Constraints.  This exception applies where topography or other similar existing site constraints necessitate the use of a platform lift as the only feasible alternative.  While the site constraint must reflect exterior conditions, the lift can be installed in the interior of a building.  For example, a new building constructed between and connected to two existing buildings may have insufficient space to coordinate floor levels and also to provide ramped entry from the public way.  In this example, an exterior or interior platform lift could be used to provide an accessible entrance or to coordinate one or more interior floor levels.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_6">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.6 Guest Rooms and Residential Dwelling Units[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to connect levels within transient lodging guest rooms required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806_2" class="navSectionLink">806.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or residential dwelling units required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_7">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.7 Amusement Rides[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide accessible routes to load and unload areas serving amusement rides.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_8">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.8 Play Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide accessible routes to play components or soft contained play structures.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_9">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.9 Team or Player Seating[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to provide accessible routes to team or player seating areas serving areas of sport activity.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 206.7.9 Team or Player Seating.  While the use of platform lifts is allowed, ramps are recommended to provide access to player seating areas serving an area of sport activity.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-206_7_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.7.10 Recreational Boating Facilities and Fishing Piers and Platforms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts shall be permitted to be used instead of gangways that are part of accessible routes serving recreational boating facilities and fishing piers and platforms.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-206_8">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]206.8 Security Barriers[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Security barriers, including but not limited to, security bollards and security check points, shall not obstruct a required accessible route or accessible means of egress.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Where security barriers incorporate elements that cannot comply with these requirements such as certain metal detectors, fluoroscopes, or other similar devices, the accessible route shall be permitted to be located adjacent to security screening devices.  The accessible route shall permit persons with disabilities passing around security barriers to maintain visual contact with their personal items to the same extent provided others passing through the security barrier.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-207">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]207 Accessible Means of Egress[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-207_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]207.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Means of egress shall comply with section 1003.2.13 of the International Building Code (2000 edition and 2001 Supplement) or section 1007 of the International Building Code (2003 edition) (incorporated by reference, see “Referenced Standards” in Chapter 1).[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-207_1x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Where means of egress are permitted by local building or life safety codes to share a common path of egress travel, accessible means of egress shall be permitted to share a common path of egress travel.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-207_1x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Areas of refuge shall not be required in detention and correctional facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-207_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]207.2 Platform Lifts[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Standby power shall be provided for platform lifts permitted by section 1003.2.13.4 of the International Building Code (2000 edition and 2001 Supplement) or section 1007.5 of the International Building Code (2003 edition) (incorporated by reference, see “Referenced Standards” in Chapter 1) to serve as a part of an accessible means of egress.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-208">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]208 Parking Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-208_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]208.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where parking spaces are provided, parking spaces shall be provided in accordance with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-208" class="navSectionLink">208</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Parking spaces used exclusively for buses, trucks, other delivery vehicles, law enforcement vehicles, or vehicular impound shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-208" class="navSectionLink">208</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]provided that lots accessed by the public are provided with a passenger loading zone complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-503" class="navSectionLink">503</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-208_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]208.2 Minimum Number[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Parking spaces complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-502" class="navSectionLink">502</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be provided in accordance with Table 208.2 except as required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-208_2_1" class="navSectionLink">208.2.1</a>, <a href="#ada-208_2_2" class="navSectionLink">208.2.2</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and 208.2.3.  Where more than one parking facility is provided on a site, the number of accessible spaces provided on the site shall be calculated according to the number of spaces required for each parking facility.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<table class="standards data"><caption>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Table 208.2 Parking Spaces[-END TRANSLATE-]</caption>
<thead>
