</tbody>
</table>
<h4 id="ada-227_2_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]227.2.1 Altered Check-Out Aisles[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where check-out aisles are altered, at least one of each check-out aisle serving each function shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_3" class="navSectionLink">904.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]until the number of check-out aisles complies with 227.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-227_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]227.3 Counters[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where provided, at least one of each type of sales counter and service counter shall comply with 904.4.  Where counters are dispersed throughout the building or facility, counters complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_4" class="navSectionLink">904.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]also shall be dispersed.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 227.3 Counters.  Types of counters that provide different services in the same facility include, but are not limited to, order, pick-up, express, and returns.  One continuous counter can be used to provide different types of service.  For example, order and pick-up are different services.  It would not be acceptable to provide access only to the part of the counter where orders are taken when orders are picked-up at a different location on the same counter.  Both the order and pick-up section of the counter must be accessible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-227_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]227.4 Food Service Lines[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Food service lines shall comply with 904.5.  Where self-service shelves are provided, at least 50 percent, but no fewer than one, of each type provided shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-308" class="navSectionLink">308</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-227_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]227.5 Queues and Waiting Lines[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Queues and waiting lines servicing counters or check-out aisles required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_3" class="navSectionLink">904.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_4" class="navSectionLink">904.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-403" class="navSectionLink">403</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-228">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]228 Depositories, Vending Machines, Change Machines, Mail Boxes, and Fuel Dispensers[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-228_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]228.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where provided, at least one of each type of depository, vending machine, change machine, and fuel dispenser shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Drive-up only depositories shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 228.1 General.  Depositories include, but are not limited to, night receptacles in banks, post offices, video stores, and libraries.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-228_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]228.2 Mail Boxes[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where mail boxes are provided in an interior location, at least 5 percent, but no fewer than one, of each type shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In residential facilities, where mail boxes are provided for each residential dwelling unit, mail boxes complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be provided for each residential dwelling unit required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-229">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]229 Windows[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-229_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]229.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where glazed openings are provided in accessible rooms or spaces for operation by occupants, at least one opening shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Each glazed opening required by an administrative authority to be operable shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-309" class="navSectionLink">309</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  1.  Glazed openings in residential dwelling units required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809" class="navSectionLink">809</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-229" class="navSectionLink">229</a>.</p>
<p class="standard">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Glazed openings in guest rooms required to provide communication features and in guest rooms required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_5_3" class="navSectionLink">206.5.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-229" class="navSectionLink">229</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-230">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]230 Two-Way Communication Systems[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-230_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]230.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where a two-way communication system is provided to gain admittance to a building or facility or to restricted areas within a building or facility, the system shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-708" class="navSectionLink">708</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 230.1 General.  This requirement applies to facilities such as office buildings, courthouses, and other facilities where admittance to the building or restricted spaces is dependent on two-way communication systems.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-231">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231 Judicial Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-231_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Judicial facilities shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-231" class="navSectionLink">231</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-231_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.2 Courtrooms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Each courtroom shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-808" class="navSectionLink">808</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-231_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.3 Holding Cells[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where provided, central holding cells and court-floor holding cells shall comply with 231.3.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-231_3_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.3.1 Central Holding Cells[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where separate central holding cells are provided for adult male, juvenile male, adult female, or juvenile female, one of each type shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where central holding cells are provided and are not separated by age or sex, at least one cell complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be provided.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-231_3_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.3.2 Court-Floor Holding Cells[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where separate court-floor holding cells are provided for adult male, juvenile male, adult female, or juvenile female, each courtroom shall be served by one cell of each type complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where court-floor holding cells are provided and are not separated by age or sex, courtrooms shall be served by at least one cell complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Cells may serve more than one courtroom.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-231_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.4 Visiting Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Visiting areas shall comply with 231.4.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-231_4_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.4.1 Cubicles and Counters[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least 5 percent, but no fewer than one, of cubicles shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-902" class="navSectionLink">902</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]on both the visitor and detainee sides.  Where counters are provided, at least one shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_4_2" class="navSectionLink">904.4.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]on both the visitor and detainee sides.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  The detainee side of cubicles or counters at non-contact visiting areas not serving holding cells required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-231" class="navSectionLink">231</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-902" class="navSectionLink">902</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_4_2" class="navSectionLink">904.4.2</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-231_4_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]231.4.2 Partitions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where solid partitions or security glazing separate visitors from detainees at least one of each type of cubicle or counter partition shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_6" class="navSectionLink">904.6</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-232">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232 Detention Facilities and Correctional Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-232_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Buildings, facilities, or portions thereof, in which people are detained for penal or correction purposes, or in which the liberty of the inmates is restricted for security reasons shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-232" class="navSectionLink">232</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 232.1 General.  Detention facilities include, but are not limited to, jails, detention centers, and holding cells in police stations.  Correctional facilities include, but are not limited to, prisons, reformatories, and correctional centers.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<table role="presentation" class="standards" style="width: 100%; background-color: #eeeeee; border: 1px solid #000000;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p class="standards"><em>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Note to Reader:[-END TRANSLATE-]</em> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The Department of Justice’s ADA standards also require the following:[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards"><strong>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Detention and correctional facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</strong> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-] (1) New construction of jails, prisons, and other detention and correctional facilities shall comply with the 2010 Standards except that public entities shall provide accessible mobility features complying with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards for a minimum of 3%, but no fewer than one, of the total number of cells in a facility. Cells with mobility features shall be provided in each classification level.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](2) Alterations to detention and correctional facilities.  Alterations to jails, prisons, and other detention and correctional facilities shall comply with the 2010 Standards except that public entities shall provide accessible mobility features complying with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards for a minimum of 3%, but no fewer than one, of the total number of cells being altered until at least 3%, but no fewer than one, of the total number of cells in a facility shall provide mobility features complying with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Altered cells with mobility features shall be provided in each classification level.  However, when alterations are made to specific cells, detention and correctional facility operators may satisfy their obligation to provide the required number of cells with mobility features by providing the required mobility features in substitute cells (cells other than those where alterations are originally planned), provided that each substitute cell—[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](i) Is located within the same prison site;[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](ii) Is integrated with other cells to the maximum extent feasible;[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](iii) Has, at a minimum, equal physical access as the altered cells to areas used by inmates or detainees for visitation, dining, recreation, educational programs, medical services, work programs, religious services, and participation in other programs that the facility offers to inmates or detainees; and,[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](iv) If it is technically infeasible to locate a substitute cell within the same prison site, a substitute cell must be provided at another prison site within the corrections system.[-END TRANSLATE-][-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](3) With respect to medical and long-term care facilities in jails, prisons, and other detention and correctional facilities, public entities shall apply the 2010 Standards technical and scoping requirements for those facilities irrespective of whether those facilities are licensed.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id="ada-232_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.2 General Holding Cells and General Housing Cells[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]General holding cells and general housing cells shall be provided in accordance with 232.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Alterations to cells shall not be required to comply except to the extent determined by the Attorney General.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 232.2 General Holding Cells and General Housing Cells.  accessible cells or rooms should be dispersed among different levels of security, housing categories, and holding classifications (e.g., male/female and adult/juvenile) to facilitate access. Many detention and correctional facilities are designed so that certain areas (e.g., “shift” areas) can be adapted to serve as different types of housing according to need.  For example, a shift area serving as a medium-security housing unit might be redesignated for a period of time as a high-security housing unit to meet capacity needs.  Placement of accessible cells or rooms in shift areas may allow additional flexibility in meeting requirements for dispersion of accessible cells or rooms.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 232.2 General Holding Cells and General Housing Cells Exception.  Although these requirements do not specify that cells be accessible as a consequence of an alteration, title II of the ADA requires that each service, program, or activity conducted by a public entity, when viewed in its entirety, be readily accessible to and usable by individuals with disabilities.  This requirement must be met unless doing so would fundamentally alter the nature of a service, program, or activity or would result in undue financial and administrative burdens.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h4 id="ada-232_2_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.2.1 Cells with Mobility Features[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least 2 percent, but no fewer than one, of the total number of cells in a facility shall provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-232_2_1_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.2.1.1 Beds[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In cells having more than 25 beds, at least 5 percent of the beds shall have clear floor space complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2_3" class="navSectionLink">807.2.3</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-232_2_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.2.2 Cells with Communication Features[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least 2 percent, but no fewer than one, of the total number of general holding cells and general housing cells equipped with audible emergency alarm systems and permanently installed telephones within the cell shall provide communication features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_3" class="navSectionLink">807.3</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-232_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.3 Special Holding Cells and Special Housing Cells[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where special holding cells or special housing cells are provided, at least one cell serving each purpose shall provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-807_2" class="navSectionLink">807.2</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Cells subject to this requirement include, but are not limited to, those used for purposes of orientation, protective custody, administrative or disciplinary detention or segregation, detoxification, and medical isolation.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Alterations to cells shall not be required to comply except to the extent determined by the Attorney General.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-232_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.4 Medical Care Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Patient bedrooms or cells required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-223" class="navSectionLink">223</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be provided in addition to any medical isolation cells required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-232_3" class="navSectionLink">232.3</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-232_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.5 Visiting Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Visiting areas shall comply with 232.5.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-232_5_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.5.1 Cubicles and Counters[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least 5 percent, but no fewer than one, of cubicles shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-902" class="navSectionLink">902</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]on both the visitor and detainee sides.  Where counters are provided, at least one shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_4_2" class="navSectionLink">904.4.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]on both the visitor and detainee or inmate sides.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  The inmate or detainee side of cubicles or counters at non-contact visiting areas not serving holding cells or housing cells required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-232" class="navSectionLink">232</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-902" class="navSectionLink">902</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_4_2" class="navSectionLink">904.4.2</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-232_5_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]232.5.2 Partitions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where solid partitions or security glazing separate visitors from detainees or inmates at least one of each type of cubicle or counter partition shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-904_6" class="navSectionLink">904.6</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-233">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233 Residential Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-233_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Facilities with residential dwelling units shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233" class="navSectionLink">233</a>.</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 233.1 General.  Section 233 outlines the requirements for residential facilities subject to the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990.  The facilities covered by Section 233, as well as other facilities not covered by this section, may still be subject to other Federal laws such as the Fair Housing Act and Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as amended.  For example, the Fair Housing Act requires that certain residential structures having four or more multi-family dwelling units, regardless of whether they are privately owned or federally assisted, include certain features of accessible and adaptable design according to guidelines established by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD).  These laws and the appropriate regulations should be consulted before proceeding with the design and construction of residential facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Residential facilities containing residential dwelling units provided by entities subject to HUD’s Section 504 regulations and residential dwelling units covered by Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3" class="navSectionLink">233.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]must comply with the technical and scoping requirements in Chapters 1 through 10 included this document.  Section 233 is not a stand-alone section; this section only addresses the minimum number of residential dwelling units within a facility required to comply with Chapter 8.  However, residential facilities must also comply with the requirements of this document.  For example:  Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_5_4" class="navSectionLink">206.5.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]requires all doors and doorways providing user passage in residential dwelling units providing mobility features to comply with Section 404; Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_7_6" class="navSectionLink">206.7.6</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]permits platform lifts to be used to connect levels within residential dwelling units providing mobility features; Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-208" class="navSectionLink">208</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]provides general scoping for accessible parking and Section 208.2.3.1 specifies the required number of accessible parking spaces for each residential dwelling unit providing mobility features; Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-228_2" class="navSectionLink">228.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]requires mail boxes to be within reach ranges when they serve residential dwelling units providing mobility features; play areas are addressed in Section 240; and swimming pools are addressed in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-242" class="navSectionLink">242</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]There are special provisions applicable to facilities containing residential dwelling units at:  Exception 3 to 202.3; Exception to 202.4; 203.8; and Exception 4 to[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206_2_3" class="navSectionLink">206.2.3</a>.</p>
</div>
<h3 id="ada-233_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.2 Residential Dwelling Units Provided by Entities Subject to HUD Section 504 Regulations[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where facilities with residential dwelling units are provided by entities subject to regulations issued by the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) under Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as amended, such entities shall provide residential dwelling units with mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]in a number required by the applicable HUD regulations.  Residential dwelling units required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be on an accessible route as required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206" class="navSectionLink">206</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In addition, such entities shall provide residential dwelling units with communication features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_5" class="navSectionLink">809.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]in a number required by the applicable HUD regulations.  Entities subject to[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_2" class="navSectionLink">233.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3" class="navSectionLink">233.3</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 233.2 Residential Dwelling Units Provided by Entities Subject to HUD Section 504 Regulations.  Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_2" class="navSectionLink">233.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]requires that entities subject to HUD’s regulations implementing Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as amended, provide residential dwelling units containing mobility features and residential dwelling units containing communication features complying with these regulations in a number specified in HUD’s Section 504 regulations.  Further, the residential dwelling units provided must be dispersed according to HUD’s Section 504 criteria.  In addition, Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_2" class="navSectionLink">233.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]defers to HUD the specification of criteria by which the technical requirements of this document will apply to alterations of existing facilities subject to HUD’s Section 504 regulations.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-233_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3 Residential Dwelling Units Provided by Entities Not Subject to HUD Section 504 Regulations[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Facilities with residential dwelling units provided by entities not subject to regulations issued by the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) under Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as amended, shall comply with 233.3.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-233_3_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.1 Minimum Number: New Construction[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Newly constructed facilities with residential dwelling units shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3_1" class="navSectionLink">233.3.1</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Where facilities contain 15 or fewer residential dwelling units, the requirements of 233.3.1.1 and 233.3.1.2 shall apply to the total number of residential dwelling units that are constructed under a single contract, or are developed as a whole, whether or not located on a common site.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h5 id="ada-233_3_1_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.1.1 Residential Dwelling Units with Mobility Features[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In facilities with residential dwelling units, at least 5 percent, but no fewer than one unit, of the total number of residential dwelling units shall provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and shall be on an accessible route as required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206" class="navSectionLink">206</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-233_3_1_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.1.2 Residential Dwelling Units with Communication Features[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In facilities with residential dwelling units, at least 2 percent, but no fewer than one unit, of the total number of residential dwelling units shall provide communication features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_5" class="navSectionLink">809.5</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-233_3_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.2 Residential Dwelling Units for Sale[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Residential dwelling units offered for sale shall provide accessible features to the extent required by regulations issued by Federal agencies under the Americans with Disabilities Act or Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as amended.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 233.3.2 Residential Dwelling Units for Sale.  A public entity that conducts a program to build housing for purchase by individual home buyers must provide access according to the requirements of the ADA regulations and a program receiving Federal financial assistance must comply with the applicable Section 504 regulation.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<table role="presentation" class="standards" style="width: 100%; background-color: #eeeeee; border: 1px solid #000000;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p class="standards"><em>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Note to Reader:[-END TRANSLATE-]</em> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The Department of Justice’s ADA standards also require the following:[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Facilities with residential dwelling units for sale to individual owners.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](1) Residential dwelling units designed and constructed or altered by public entities that will be offered for sale to individuals shall comply with the requirements for residential facilities in the 2010 Standards including sections[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233" class="navSectionLink">233</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809" class="navSectionLink">809</a>.</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](2) The requirements of paragraph (1) also apply to housing programs that are operated by public entities where design and construction of particular residential dwelling units takes place only after a specific buyer has been identified. In such programs, the covered entity must provide the units that comply with the requirements for accessible features to those pre-identified buyers with disabilities who have requested such a unit.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h4 id="ada-233_3_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.3 Additions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where an addition to an existing building results in an increase in the number of residential dwelling units, the requirements of[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3_1" class="navSectionLink">233.3.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall apply only to the residential dwelling units that are added until the total number of residential dwelling units complies with the minimum number required by 233.3.1.  Residential dwelling units required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3_1_1" class="navSectionLink">233.3.1.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be on an accessible route as required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206" class="navSectionLink">206</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-233_3_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.4 Alterations[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Alterations shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3_4" class="navSectionLink">233.3.4</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Where compliance with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a>, <a href="#ada-809_3" class="navSectionLink">809.3</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]is technically infeasible, or where it is technically infeasible to provide an accessible route to a residential dwelling unit, the entity shall be permitted to alter or construct a comparable residential dwelling unit to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]provided that the minimum number of residential dwelling units required by 233.3.1.1 and 233.3.1.2, as applicable, is satisfied.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 233.3.4 Alterations Exception.  A substituted dwelling unit must be comparable to the dwelling unit that is not made accessible.  Factors to be considered in comparing one dwelling unit to another should include the number of bedrooms; amenities provided within the dwelling unit; types of common spaces provided within the facility; and location with respect to community resources and services, such as public transportation and civic, recreational, and mercantile facilities.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h5 id="ada-233_3_4_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.4.1 Alterations to Vacated Buildings[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where a building is vacated for the purposes of alteration, and the altered building contains more than 15 residential dwelling units, at least 5 percent of the residential dwelling units shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and shall be on an accessible route as required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206" class="navSectionLink">206</a>. [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In addition, at least 2 percent of the residential dwelling units shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_5" class="navSectionLink">809.5</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 233.3.4.1 Alterations to Vacated Buildings.  This provision is intended to apply where a building is vacated with the intent to alter the building.  Buildings that are vacated solely for pest control or asbestos removal are not subject to the requirements to provide residential dwelling units with mobility features or communication features.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h5 id="ada-233_3_4_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.4.2 Alterations to Individual Residential Dwelling Units[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]In individual residential dwelling units, where a bathroom or a kitchen is substantially altered, and at least one other room is altered, the requirements of[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3_1" class="navSectionLink">233.3.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall apply to the altered residential dwelling units until the total number of residential dwelling units complies with the minimum number required by 233.3.1.1 and 233.3.1.2. Residential dwelling units required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233_3_1_1" class="navSectionLink">233.3.1.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be on an accessible route as required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-206" class="navSectionLink">206</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Where facilities contain 15 or fewer residential dwelling units, the requirements of 233.3.1.1 and 233.3.1.2 shall apply to the total number of residential dwelling units that are altered under a single contract, or are developed as a whole, whether or not located on a common site.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 233.3.4.2 Alterations to Individual Residential Dwelling Units.  Section 233.3.4.2 uses the terms “substantially altered” and “altered.”  A substantial alteration to a kitchen or bathroom includes, but is not limited to, alterations that are changes to or rearrangements in the plan configuration, or replacement of cabinetry.  Substantial alterations do not include normal maintenance or appliance and fixture replacement, unless such maintenance or replacement requires changes to or rearrangements in the plan configuration, or replacement of cabinetry.  The term “alteration” is defined both in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-106" class="navSectionLink">106</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of these requirements and in the Department of Justice ADA regulations.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-233_3_5">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]233.3.5 Dispersion[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Residential dwelling units required to provide mobility features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]through[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_4" class="navSectionLink">809.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and residential dwelling units required to provide communication features complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_5" class="navSectionLink">809.5</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be dispersed among the various types of residential dwelling units in the facility and shall provide choices of residential dwelling units comparable to, and integrated with, those available to other residents.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Where multi-story residential dwelling units are one of the types of residential dwelling units provided, one-story residential dwelling units shall be permitted as a substitute for multi-story residential dwelling units where equivalent spaces and amenities are provided in the one-story residential dwelling unit.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<table role="presentation"  class="standards" style="width: 100%; background-color: #eeeeee; border: 1px solid #000000;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p class="standards"><em>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Note to Reader:[-END TRANSLATE-]</em> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The Department of Justice’s ADA standards also require the following:[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards"><strong>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Social service center establishments.[-END TRANSLATE-]</strong> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Group homes, halfway houses, shelters, or similar social service center establishments that provide either temporary sleeping accommodations or residential dwelling units that are subject to this part [of the title III regulation or to this section of the title II regulation] shall comply with the provisions of the 2010 Standards applicable to residential facilities, including, but not limited to, the provisions in sections[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233" class="navSectionLink">233</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809" class="navSectionLink">809</a>.</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](1) In sleeping rooms with more than 25 beds covered by this part [of the title III regulation or to this section of the title II regulation], a minimum of 5% of the beds shall have clear floor space complying with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806_2_3" class="navSectionLink">806.2.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](2) Facilities with more than 50 beds covered by this part [of the title III regulation or to this section of the title II regulation] that provide common use bathing facilities shall provide at least one roll-in shower with a seat that complies with the relevant provisions of section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-608" class="navSectionLink">608</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards.  Transfer-type showers are not permitted in lieu of a roll-in shower with a seat, and the exceptions in sections[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-608_3" class="navSectionLink">608.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-608_4" class="navSectionLink">608.4</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]for residential dwelling units are not permitted.  When separate shower facilities are provided for men and for women, at least one roll-in shower shall be provided for each group.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]The Department of Justice’s ADA standards also require the following:[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards"><strong>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Housing at a place of education.[-END TRANSLATE-]</strong> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Housing at a place of education that is subject to this part [of the title III regulation or to this section of the title II regulation] shall comply with the provisions of the 2010 Standards applicable to transient lodging, including, but not limited to, the requirements for transient lodging guest rooms in sections[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-224" class="navSectionLink">224</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-806" class="navSectionLink">806</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]subject to the following exceptions. For the purposes of the application of this section, the term “sleeping room” is intended to be used interchangeably with the term “guest room” as it is used in the transient lodging standards.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](1) Kitchens within housing units containing accessible sleeping rooms with mobility features (including suites and clustered sleeping rooms) or on floors containing accessible sleeping rooms with mobility features shall provide turning spaces that comply with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards and kitchen work surfaces that comply with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-804_3" class="navSectionLink">804.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](2) Multi-bedroom housing units containing accessible sleeping rooms with mobility features shall have an accessible route throughout the unit in accordance with section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809_2" class="navSectionLink">809.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-](3) Apartments or townhouse facilities that are provided by or on behalf of a place of education, which are leased on a year-round basis exclusively to graduate students or faculty and do not contain any public use or common use areas available for educational programming, are not subject to the transient lodging standards and shall comply with the requirements for residential facilities in sections[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-233" class="navSectionLink">233</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]and[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-809" class="navSectionLink">809</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]of the 2010 Standards.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2 id="ada-234">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234 Amusement Rides[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-234_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Amusement rides shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-234" class="navSectionLink">234</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  Mobile or portable amusement rides shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-234" class="navSectionLink">234</a>.</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 234.1 General.  These requirements apply generally to newly designed and constructed amusement rides and attractions.  A custom designed and constructed ride is new upon its first use, which is the first time amusement park patrons take the ride.  With respect to amusement rides purchased from other entities, new refers to the first permanent installation of the ride, whether it is used off the shelf or modified before it is installed.  Where amusement rides are moved after several seasons to another area of the park or to another park, the ride would not be considered newly designed or newly constructed.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Some amusement rides and attractions that have unique designs and features are not addressed by these requirements.  In those situations, these requirements are to be applied to the extent possible.  An example of an amusement ride not specifically addressed by these requirements includes “virtual reality” rides where the device does not move through a fixed course within a defined area.  An accessible route must be provided to these rides.  Where an attraction or ride has unique features for which there are no applicable scoping provisions, then a reasonable number, but at least one, of the features must be located on an accessible route.  Where there are appropriate technical provisions, they must be applied to the elements that are covered by the scoping provisions.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 234.1 General Exception.  Mobile or temporary rides are those set up for short periods of time such as traveling carnivals, State and county fairs, and festivals.  The amusement rides that are covered by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-234_1" class="navSectionLink">234.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]are ones that are not regularly assembled and disassembled.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h3 id="ada-234_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234.2 Load and Unload Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Load and unload areas serving amusement rides shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_3" class="navSectionLink">1002.3</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-234_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234.3 Minimum Number[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Amusement rides shall provide at least one wheelchair space complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_4" class="navSectionLink">1002.4</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or at least one amusement ride seat designed for transfer complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_5" class="navSectionLink">1002.5</a>, [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]or at least one transfer device complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_6" class="navSectionLink">1002.6</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-234_3x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Amusement rides that are controlled or operated by the rider shall not be required to comply with 234.3.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-234_3x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  Amusement rides designed primarily for children, where children are assisted on and off the ride by an adult, shall not be required to comply with 234.3.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-234_3x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  Amusement rides that do not provide amusement ride seats shall not be required to comply with 234.3.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 234.3 Minimum Number Exceptions 1 through 3.  Amusement rides controlled or operated by the rider, designed for children, or rides without ride seats are not required to comply with 234.3.  These rides are not exempt from the other provisions in[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-234" class="navSectionLink">234</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]requiring an accessible route to the load and unload areas and to the ride.  The exception does not apply to those rides where patrons may cause the ride to make incidental movements, but where the patron otherwise has no control over the ride.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 234.3 Minimum Number Exception 2.  The exception is limited to those rides designed “primarily” for children, where children are assisted on and off the ride by an adult.  This exception is limited to those rides designed for children and not for the occasional adult user.  An accessible route to and turning space in the load and unload area will provide access for adults and family members assisting children on and off these rides.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h3 id="ada-234_4">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234.4 Existing Amusement Rides[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where existing amusement rides are altered, the alteration shall comply with 234.4.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 234.4 Existing Amusement Rides.  Routine maintenance, painting, and changing of theme boards are examples of activities that do not constitute an alteration subject to this section.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-234_4_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234.4.1 Load and Unload Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where load and unload areas serving existing amusement rides are newly designed and constructed, the load and unload areas shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1002_3" class="navSectionLink">1002.3</a>.</p>
<h4 id="ada-234_4_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]234.4.2 Minimum Number[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where the structural or operational characteristics of an amusement ride are altered to the extent that the amusement ride’s performance differs from that specified by the manufacturer or the original design, the amusement ride shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-234_3" class="navSectionLink">234.3</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-235">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]235 Recreational Boating Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-235_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]235.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Recreational boating facilities shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-235" class="navSectionLink">235</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-235_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]235.2 Boat Slips[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Boat slips complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1003_3_1" class="navSectionLink">1003.3.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be provided in accordance with Table 235.2.  Where the number of boat slips is not identified, each 40 feet (12 m) of boat slip edge provided along the perimeter of the pier shall be counted as one boat slip for the purpose of this section.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<table class="standards data"><caption>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Table 235.2 Boat Slips[-END TRANSLATE-]</caption>
<thead>
<tr><th scope="col">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Total Number of Boat Slips Provided in Facility[-END TRANSLATE-]</th><th scope="col">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Minimum Number of Required accessible Boat Slips[-END TRANSLATE-]</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]1 to 25[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]26 to 50[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]51 to 100[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>3</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]101 to 150[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>4</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]151 to 300[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>5</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]301 to 400[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>6</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]401 to 500[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>7</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]501 to 600[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>8</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]601 to 700[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>9</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]701 to 800[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>10</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]801 to 900[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>11</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]901 to 1000[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>12</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]1001 and over[-END TRANSLATE-]</th>
<td>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]12, plus 1 for every 100, or fraction thereof, over 1000[-END TRANSLATE-]</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 235.2 Boat Slips.  The requirement for boat slips also applies to piers where boat slips are not demarcated.  For example, a single pier 25 feet (7620 mm) long and 5 feet (1525 mm) wide (the minimum width specified by Section 1003.3) allows boats to moor on three sides.  Because the number of boat slips is not demarcated, the total length of boat slip edge (55 feet, 17 m) must be used to determine the number of boat slips provided (two).  This number is based on the specification in Section[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-235_2" class="navSectionLink">235.2</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]that each 40 feet (12 m) of boat slip edge, or fraction thereof, counts as one boat slip.  In this example, Table 235.2 would require one boat slip to be accessible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-235_2_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]235.2.1 Dispersion[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Boat slips complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1003_3_1" class="navSectionLink">1003.3.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be dispersed throughout the various types of boat slips provided.  Where the minimum number of boat slips required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1003_3_1" class="navSectionLink">1003.3.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]has been met, no further dispersion shall be required.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 235.2.1 Dispersion.  Types of boat slips are based on the size of the boat slips; whether single berths or double berths, shallow water or deep water, transient or longer-term lease, covered or uncovered; and whether slips are equipped with features such as telephone, water, electricity or cable connections.  The term “boat slip” is intended to cover any pier area other than launch ramp boarding piers where recreational boats are moored for purposes of berthing, embarking, or disembarking.  For example, a fuel pier may contain boat slips, and this type of short term slip would be included in determining compliance with 235.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-235_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]235.3 Boarding Piers at Boat Launch Ramps[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where boarding piers are provided at boat launch ramps, at least 5 percent, but no fewer than one, of the boarding piers shall comply with 1003.3.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-236">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]236 Exercise Machines and Equipment[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-236_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]236.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least one of each type of exercise machine and equipment shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1004" class="navSectionLink">1004</a>.</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 236.1 General.  Most strength training equipment and machines are considered different types.  Where operators provide a biceps curl machine and cable-cross-over machine, both machines are required to meet the provisions in this section, even though an individual may be able to work on their biceps through both types of equipment.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Similarly, there are many types of cardiovascular exercise machines, such as stationary bicycles, rowing machines, stair climbers, and treadmills.  Each machine provides a cardiovascular exercise and is considered a different type for purposes of these requirements.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h2 id="ada-237">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]237 Fishing Piers and Platforms[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-237_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]237.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Fishing piers and platforms shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1005" class="navSectionLink">1005</a>.</p>
<h2 id="ada-238">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238 Golf Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-238_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Golf facilities shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-238" class="navSectionLink">238</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-238_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238.2 Golf Courses[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Golf courses shall comply with 238.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-238_2_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238.2.1 Teeing Grounds[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where one teeing ground is provided for a hole, the teeing ground shall be designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit the teeing ground.  Where two teeing grounds are provided for a hole, the forward teeing ground shall be designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit the teeing ground. Where three or more teeing grounds are provided for a hole, at least two teeing grounds, including the forward teeing ground, shall be designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit each teeing ground.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  In existing golf courses, the forward teeing ground shall not be required to be one of the teeing grounds on a hole designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit the teeing ground where compliance is not feasible due to terrain.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-238_2_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238.2.2 Putting Greens[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Putting greens shall be designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit the putting green.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-238_2_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238.2.3 Weather Shelters[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where provided, weather shelters shall be designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit the weather shelter and shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1006_4" class="navSectionLink">1006.4</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-238_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]238.3 Practice Putting Greens, Practice Teeing Grounds, and Teeing Stations at Driving Ranges[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least 5 percent, but no fewer than one, of practice putting greens, practice teeing grounds, and teeing stations at driving ranges shall be designed and constructed so that a golf car can enter and exit the practice putting greens, practice teeing grounds, and teeing stations at driving ranges.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-239">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]239 Miniature Golf Facilities[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-239_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]239.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Miniature golf facilities shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-239" class="navSectionLink">239</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ada-239_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]239.2 Minimum Number[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]At least 50 percent of holes on miniature golf courses shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1007_3" class="navSectionLink">1007.3</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 239.2 Minimum Number.  Where possible, providing access to all holes on a miniature golf course is recommended.  If a course is designed with the minimum 50 percent accessible holes, designers or operators are encouraged to select holes which provide for an equivalent experience to the maximum extent possible.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-239_3">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]239.3 Miniature Golf Course Configuration[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Miniature golf courses shall be configured so that the holes complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1007_3" class="navSectionLink">1007.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]are consecutive.  Miniature golf courses shall provide an accessible route from the last hole complying with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1007_3" class="navSectionLink">1007.3</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]to the course entrance or exit without requiring travel through any other holes on the course.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  One break in the sequence of consecutive holes shall be permitted provided that the last hole on the miniature golf course is the last hole in the sequence.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 239.3 Miniature Golf Course Configuration.  Where only the minimum 50 percent of the holes are accessible, an accessible route from the last accessible hole to the course exit or entrance must not require travel back through other holes.  In some cases, this may require an additional accessible route.  Other options include increasing the number of accessible holes in a way that limits the distance needed to connect the last accessible hole with the course exit or entrance.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h2 id="ada-240">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240 Play Areas[-END TRANSLATE-]</h2>
<h3 id="ada-240_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240.1 General[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Play areas for children ages 2 and over shall comply with 240.  Where separate play areas are provided within a site for specific age groups, each play area shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240" class="navSectionLink">240</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-240_1x1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTIONS:  1.  Play areas located in family child care facilities where the proprietor actually resides shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240" class="navSectionLink">240</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-240_1x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]2.  In existing play areas, where play components are relocated for the purposes of creating safe use zones and the ground surface is not altered or extended for more than one use zone, the play area shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240" class="navSectionLink">240</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-240_1x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]3.  Amusement attractions shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240" class="navSectionLink">240</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions" id="ada-240_1x">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]4.  Where play components are altered and the ground surface is not altered, the ground surface shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1008_2_6" class="navSectionLink">1008.2.6</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]unless required by[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-202_4" class="navSectionLink">202.4</a>.</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 240.1 General.  Play areas may be located on exterior sites or within a building.  Where separate play areas are provided within a site for children in specified age groups (e.g., preschool (ages 2 to 5) and school age (ages 5 to 12)), each play area must comply with this section.  Where play areas are provided for the same age group on a site but are geographically separated (e.g., one is located next to a picnic area and another is located next to a softball field), they are considered separate play areas and each play area must comply with this section.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-240_1_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240.1.1 Additions[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where play areas are designed and constructed in phases, the requirements of 240 shall apply to each successive addition so that when the addition is completed, the entire play area complies with all the applicable requirements of 240.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="advisory">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 240.1.1 Additions.  These requirements are to be applied so that when each successive addition is completed, the entire play area complies with all applicable provisions.  For example, a play area is built in two phases.  In the first phase, there are 10 elevated play components and 10 elevated play components are added in the second phase for a total of 20 elevated play components in the play area.  When the first phase was completed, at least 5 elevated play components, including at least 3 different types, were to be provided on an accessible route.  When the second phase is completed, at least 10 elevated play components must be located on an accessible route, and at least 7 ground level play components, including 4 different types, must be provided on an accessible route.  At the time the second phase is complete, ramps must be used to connect at least 5 of the elevated play components and transfer systems are permitted to be used to connect the rest of the elevated play components required to be located on an accessible route.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h3 id="ada-240_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240.2 Play Components[-END TRANSLATE-]</h3>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where provided, play components shall comply with 240.2.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<h4 id="ada-240_2_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240.2.1 Ground Level Play Components[-END TRANSLATE-]</h4>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Ground level play components shall be provided in the number and types required by 240.2.1.  Ground level play components that are provided to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240_2_1_1" class="navSectionLink">240.2.1.1</a> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]shall be permitted to satisfy the additional number required by 240.2.1.2 if the minimum required types of play components are satisfied.  Where two or more required ground level play components are provided, they shall be dispersed throughout the play area and integrated with other play components.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<div class="advisory">
<p class="first">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Advisory 240.2.1 Ground Level Play Components.  Examples of ground level play components may include spring rockers, swings, diggers, and stand-alone slides.  When distinguishing between the different types of ground level play components, consider the general experience provided by the play component.  Examples of different types of experiences include, but are not limited to, rocking, swinging, climbing, spinning, and sliding.  A spiral slide may provide a slightly different experience from a straight slide, but sliding is the general experience and therefore a spiral slide is not considered a different type of play component from a straight slide.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Ground level play components accessed by children with disabilities must be integrated into the play area.  Designers should consider the optimal layout of ground level play components accessed by children with disabilities to foster interaction and socialization among all children. Grouping all ground level play components accessed by children with disabilities in one location is not considered integrated.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where a stand-alone slide is provided, an accessible route must connect the base of the stairs at the entry point to the exit point of the slide.  A ramp or transfer system to the top of the slide is not required.  Where a sand box is provided, an accessible route must connect to the border of the sand box.  Accessibility to the sand box would be enhanced by providing a transfer system into the sand or by providing a raised sand table with knee clearance complying with 1008.4.3.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Ramps are preferred over transfer systems since not all children who use wheelchairs or other mobility devices may be able to use, or may choose not to use, transfer systems.  Where ramps connect elevated play components, the maximum rise of any ramp run is limited to 12 inches (305 mm).  Where possible, designers and operators are encouraged to provide ramps with a slope less than the 1:12 maximum.  Berms or sculpted dirt may be used to provide elevation and may be part of an accessible route to composite play structures.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
<p class="last">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Platform lifts are permitted as a part of an accessible route.  Because lifts must be independently operable, operators should carefully consider the appropriateness of their use in unsupervised settings.[-END TRANSLATE-]</p>
</div>
<h5 id="ada-240_2_1_1">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240.2.1.1 Minimum Number and Types[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where ground level play components are provided, at least one of each type shall be on an accessible route and shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1008_4" class="navSectionLink">1008.4</a>.</p>
<h5 id="ada-240_2_1_2">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]240.2.1.2 Additional Number and Types[-END TRANSLATE-]</h5>
<p class="standards">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Where elevated play components are provided, ground level play components shall be provided in accordance with Table 240.2.1.2 and shall comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-1008_4" class="navSectionLink">1008.4</a>.</p>
<p class="standards exceptions">[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]EXCEPTION:  If at least 50 percent of the elevated play components are connected by a ramp and at least 3 of the elevated play components connected by the ramp are different types of play components, the play area shall not be required to comply with[-END TRANSLATE-] <a href="#ada-240_2_1_2" class="navSectionLink">240.2.1.2</a>.</p>
<table class="standards data"><caption>[-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Table 240.2.1.2 Number and Types of Ground Level Play[-END TRANSLATE] <br> [-BEGIN TRANSLATE-]Components Required to be on accessible Routes[-END TRANSLATE] <small><br> </small></caption>
